<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="7">
<HEAD>THE TIMES.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE, <HI>A Dre&s;&s;ing-room, Books, Mu&s;ic, Clothes &s;cattered about.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Mr.</HI> WOODLEY <HI>dre&s;&s;ing,</HI> FORWARD <HI>at a di&s;tance.</HI></STAGE>
<P>SURE, never man was &s;o &s;uddenly involved as I have been!&mdash;and yet I cannot charge either my wife or my&s;elf with any particular extravagance. We do but live like other people of our rank; and yet, in le&s;s than four years that we have been mar|ried, an e&s;tate of four thou&s;and pounds a-year has dwindled into nothing!&mdash;Heigh-ho!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(ob&s;erving</HI> Forward <HI>li&s;tening, he hums a tune)</HI></STAGE>&mdash;I can neither get this Air into my head, or out of it.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am often plagued &s;o, my&s;elf, Sir, after the fir&s;t night of a new Opera, tho' I have a to|lerable ear, and catch a tune pretty readily.</P>
<PB N="2" REF="8">
<STAGE><HI>Enter a Footman, and delivers a Letter to Mr.</HI> Woodley. <HI>He reads it, and appears agitated.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a propo&s;al!&mdash;I would die fir&s;t. Get me pen, ink, and paper</P>
<STAGE>(throws the letter on the table).</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
<P>I'll fetch them in&s;tantly from the Library, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You need not. I'll write there.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;eems devili&s;hly flurried by that &s;ame letter. I wi&s;h I could come fairly at its con|tents. 'Tis no billet-doux, I am certain; for I have never found him tripping that way, &s;ince I have been in the family. It mu&s;t be &s;ome matter of bu|&s;ine&s;s, and if it is, it may concern me as well as my ma&s;ter. I have had my doubts that our affairs were going wrong, for &s;ome months pa&s;t. Our hall has been crowded with &s;turdy Trade&s;men, and we have had &s;neaking Jews clo&s;eted in the Library.&mdash;Egad, I'll venture; for where intere&s;t is concerned, even my honour mu&s;t give way&mdash; <STAGE>(takes up the letter).</STAGE> He may &s;urpri&s;e me, tho'.&mdash;I wi&s;h his &s;hoes creaked <STAGE>(looks out and li&s;tens).</STAGE>&mdash;No&mdash;all's &s;afe yet; and now for the indulgence of a rea&s;onable curio&s;ity.&mdash; <STAGE>(reads.)</STAGE> 
<LETTER>
<P>I find it impo&s;&s;ible to trifle any longer with your creditors; the executions will therefore immedi|ately be laid on, unle&s;s you can prevail on Lady Mary to relea&s;e her jointure; for there is not even a Jew in Duke's-Place that will advance a guinea more on your e&s;tate, whil&s;t that incumbrance re|mains.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>I am your humble &s;ervant, JOHN FLEECE'EM.</SIGNED>
<POSTSCRIPT>
<P>P. S. I have &s;carce ca&s;h enough in my hands to di&s;charge the inclo&s;ed &s;mall bill of co&s;ts.</P>
</POSTSCRIPT></CLOSER>
</LETTER></P>
<P>Here's a bill, as long as his Taylor's!</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Woodley.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Puppy! What are you meddling with
<PB N="3" REF="9">
tho&s;e papers for? Give this letter to James, and order him to carry it in&s;tantly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I not put the things to rights, fir&s;t, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do as I order you, and leave the room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, and the place, too, as &s;oon as your Honour can provide your&s;elf. <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> I &s;hould not chu&s;e to depend upon a <HI>po&s;t obit</HI> for my wages.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>How &s;hall I be able to reveal my &s;itua|tion to Lady Mary! My heart bleeds for what &s;he mu&s;t &s;uffer!</P>
<STAGE>Enter a Footman.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Footman.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel Mountfort, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>De&s;ire him to walk in.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Colonel</HI> Mountfort.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good-morrow, Woodley! What, not dre&s;&s;ed yet! I expected to find you booted, and ready to &s;et out for Newmarket. You'll be late on the turf. Your hor&s;es run, I &s;uppo&s;e? What matches have you made?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>None, Colonel. I &s;hall not be there, this Meeting.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You amaze me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>Would I had never been there! I am &s;ick of the diver&s;ion, and &s;hall never make another bett on the turf while I live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you di&s;po&s;e of your &s;tud, then? It mu&s;t be an enormous, and now an u&s;ele&s;s expence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hor&s;es are the lea&s;t part of the extrava|gances incident to racing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is <HI>&s;elon,</HI> Woodley; for I have known &s;everal fortunes made on the turf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>True&mdash;but by tho&s;e only who had none to lo&s;e. They are &s;ure&s;t to win, who carry lea&s;t weight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="10">
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take my advice, then, and &s;ell your hor&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, faith, I wi&s;h they were di&s;po&s;ed of. But yet, I don't know, I &s;hould be a&s;hamed, I think, to adverti&s;e them, as it might look &s;ome-how as if one could not afford to keep them. Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ridiculous &s;uppo&s;ition!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ridiculous, indeed! That you know, Mountfort, is far from the ca&s;e, but I really am tired of the &s;port; and the Meeting, too, is at a time of the year when there are &s;o many more agreeable amu&s;ements to be met with in London, &s;o that I &s;hould be glad to get rid of them, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me di&s;po&s;e of them for you, then. I'll be your Auctioneer, and try if I can't emblazon their pedigree with a little of that true humour which Charles Surface be&s;tows on his ance&s;tors, when he &s;ets up their pictures to &s;ale. Bucephalus, the fa|mous Bucephalus, Gentlemen, de&s;cended in a right line from the renowned quadrupede of that name, which had the honour of carrying a greater brute than him&s;elf&mdash;the immortal Alexander&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo! Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Or &s;hall we deduce his lineage from&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You had better con&s;ult Tatter&s;all, for their pedigree, as he is your only herald in tho&s;e points. Heigh-ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heigh-ho! This is but poor encourage|ment for me to enter on my new profe&s;&s;ion. Surely there is &s;omething malignant in the air, at pre&s;ent; for every man I have conver&s;ed with, this morning, &s;eems rather to be depre&s;&s;ed with the gloom of November, than enlivened by the &s;un&s;hine of April. I have ju&s;t now left Jack Knightly and Will Carele&s;s calculating, not their nativities, but their deaths.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aw them both at Boodle's, ye&s;terday, in good health.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not the more likely to live, for that, I a&s;|&s;ure you. However, it was not their natural exi&s;t|ence,
<PB N="5" REF="11">
but their nece&s;&s;ary &s;ub&s;i&s;tence, that employed their mathematics.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You a&s;toni&s;h me!&mdash;Why, it is but lately they came into po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of great e&s;tates.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>True:&mdash;but then they have travelled the modern &s;hort and ea&s;y road to ruin, of granting annuities for this twelvemonth pa&s;t, and are now &s;o nearly arrived at the la&s;t &s;tage of their journey, that I think Jack &s;aid he had but two months to run; and Will flattered him&s;elf, that as the &s;ummer was approaching, he might be able to hold out four. I advi&s;ed their compounding the terms, and run|ning together for three months each.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor fellows! I am &s;orry for them. <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Would I could promi&s;e my&s;elf even &s;o long a reprieve.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! moping again, Woodley? You'll infect me, if I &s;tay.&mdash;Where are the Ladies?&mdash;In truth, my vi&s;it was to them, for I &s;carce hoped to find you here. Are Lady Mary and your &s;i&s;ter vi&s;ible? or &s;hall I pa&s;s on to your Uncle's apartment, and pay my re&s;pects to him? I think there is a door of communication to his hou&s;e from this room. Shall I go this way?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That may be a &s;ervice of danger, Colonel; for I fear Sir William is not at pre&s;ent much delighted either with his vicinity, or affinity, to any of this family, except my &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am glad to hear you can except my &s;weet Loui&s;a; for, notwith&s;tanding the bru&s;quene&s;s of his manners, I have &s;uch an opinion of the old Knight's good &s;en&s;e and good nature, that I cannot readily acquit tho&s;e he is offended with, as wholly free from blame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ub&s;cribe to your cen&s;ure, as far as it relates to my&s;elf; but the a&s;perity of his behaviour to Lady Mary, renders me extremely unhappy; and not even my pa&s;t obligations, or future pro&s;pects,
<PB N="6" REF="12">
&s;hall ever make me acquie&s;ce in his treating my wife with di&s;re&s;pect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Allow me to &s;ay, Woodley, that per&s;ons &s;o nearly connected, ought to di&s;pen&s;e with ceremony, in favour of &s;incerity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's a dangerous tenet, Colonel, and may be extended 'till downright rudene&s;s may be con&s;idered but as the privilege of family-chat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think you have no cau&s;e for &s;uch an appre|hen&s;ion, in this ca&s;e, as Sir William is quite as &s;ingular for goodne&s;s of heart, as for a deficiency in that outward varni&s;h which too often &s;upplies the place of it. But to compound the argument, let us admit there may be faults on both &s;ides.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Mary, <HI>and</HI> Loui&s;a.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Woodley, don't I look like a hag, to-day? Do you know that I have not &s;lept an hour, the whole night!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm &s;orry for it, my dear:&mdash;I hope it was not any illne&s;s that prevented your re&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I was not the lea&s;t ill; but the uncommon brilliancy of Lady Mu&s;hroom's ear-rings, that I &s;aw at the Opera, in the evening, twinkled all night before my eyes, and would not &s;uffer me to clo&s;e them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vanity has her vigils, I perceive, Ladies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's but fair, Colonel, as her fe&s;tivals &s;eem to be&s;tow &s;uch &s;upreme delight on her votaries of both &s;exes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think, now, that a thou&s;and pounds added to my own, would make them out-blaze Lady Mu&s;hroom's; and I am &s;ure my dear Woodley won't refu&s;e me &s;uch a trifle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can refu&s;e you nothing&mdash;but we'll talk of it &s;ome other time.</P>
<PB N="7" REF="13">
<STAGE><HI>Enter a Servant and delivers a Letter to Mr.</HI> Woodley, <HI>which he ju&s;t runs his eye over, and puts up.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>What makes you look &s;o grave, my Love? I &s;hould almo&s;t &s;uppo&s;e that letter was from your Uncle, if he did not live in the &s;ame hou&s;e, and had not a peculiar delight in &s;eeing the effect of his own ill temper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>The reprehen&s;ions of &s;incere friends pro|ceed oftener from kindne&s;s, than ill-nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to Woodley.)</STAGE>
<P>Will you &s;end for Set|well to-morrow, my Dear, if you are not at lei&s;ure to-day? I mu&s;t have this bar taken out, the middle &s;tone larger, and the drop at lea&s;t twice this &s;ize: and pray hurry him, for I mu&s;t po&s;itively wear them at Court, next Sunday.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(mu&s;ing)</STAGE>
<P>It mu&s;t be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You don't attend to me, Mr. Woodley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, yes, my Dear, I hear every word you &s;ay. Give me the ear-rings, I'll carry them my&s;elf to the Jeweller.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here they are;&mdash;but don't be too extravagant:&mdash;I would not have more than a thou&s;and pounds added, on any account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>I give you credit for that la&s;t caution, Lady Mary; as 'tis uncommon to hear a wife re|&s;training her hu&s;band's genero&s;ity to her&s;elf, in this day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>His indulgence, Colonel, has ever exceeded my wi&s;hes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>But never equalled my own. <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> My heart is breaking for her.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter a Servant, who gives a printed Paper to Lady</HI> Mary.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>With Mrs. Bromley's compliments, Madam, and reque&s;ts you'll do her the honour to call on her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! 'tis the Catalogue &s;he promi&s;ed to mark for me. My compliments, and I &s;hall be at her door in a few minutes.&mdash;Loui&s;a, are you di&s;|po&s;ed for Chri&s;t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">e's Rooms, this morning? There are abundance of fine things, and, of cour&s;e, fine people, to be there. I delight in an Auction, one meets with &s;o many things there, one never thought one wanted before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Though it is not my pa&s;&s;ion, I'll attend your Lady&s;hip with plea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(looking over the Catalogue)</STAGE>
<P>See, Wood|ley, what an uncon&s;cionable creature Bromley is! She has marked a whole &s;ide of the Catalogue.&mdash;A lu&s;tre that holds a hundred lights! I think I &s;hould like that, now, for our grand &s;aloon, in the country. I own, I &s;hould delight va&s;tly to a&s;toni&s;h our neigh|bours in Dor&s;et&s;hire&mdash;if ever we go there. Have you any objection, my Dear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>But one, my Dear&mdash;I am to &s;ettle with my Banker, to day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter&mdash;Mrs. Bromley &s;hall be my Banker. Her pur&s;e is always at the &s;ervice of her friends.&mdash;O, here's the &s;weete&s;t &s;ett of fillagree dre&s;&s;ing-plate!&mdash;I mu&s;t have that, Woodley, in&s;tead of the one I have had the&s;e two years.&mdash;'Tis ab&s;o|lutely Gothic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>I cannot wound her by re&s;traint.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you think Mrs. Bromley a de|lightful creature, Colonel?&mdash;<Q>Two of the large&s;t Seve va&s;es that have ever been imported.</Q> I po|&s;itively mu&s;t have them. How good it was in the dear Bromley to note the&s;e articles!&mdash;Why don't you tell me how you like my friend?</P>
<STAGE>(To the Colonel.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not the honour, Madam, of knowing her &s;ufficiently to judge of her character, and there|fore can only &s;peak of it as doubtful.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doubtful, Colonel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>In &s;ome ca&s;es, Lady Mary, to doubt, is rather to compliment, than to cen&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="15">
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, in other ca&s;es, to doubt, is to be cer|tain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You don't affect to be doubtful, I hope, Mi&s;s Woodley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means, I a&s;&s;ure you. Mrs. Brom|ley's character is quite clear to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you talk in this &s;tile, Loui&s;a, I &s;hall certainly conclude that you are jealous of the dear Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not on what account I &s;hould be &s;o, except in your good graces; for I hope you don't think me vain enough to attempt rivalling her with her pre&s;ent Ceci&s;beo, Sir Harry Granger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>That ridiculous compound of affectation and epicuri&s;m! who ruminates upon every meal, and tries to pre&s;erve the reli&s;h of his &s;auces, by a repetition of their ingredients in every new com|pany that admits him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are mon&s;trou&s;ly cen&s;orious, Colo|nel; but I will allow that he is a little out of fa&s;hion, at pre&s;ent; and for that rea&s;on, I have forbidden his ever coming into this hou&s;e. The Bromleys dine here to-day, my Dear <STAGE>(to Mr. Woodley.)</STAGE>&mdash;But we lo&s;e time. The Auction may begin, and &s;ome of the dear things I have &s;et my heart upon be gone before we get there.&mdash;I &s;hall never forget that old frightful Mandarin, Lord Gobble, for whipping up the Seve China <HI>Dejeuner</HI> from me, at the la&s;t &s;ale.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will your Lady&s;hip permit me to have the honour of attending you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a vacant &s;eat in the coach, and you &s;hall be welcome, if you won't be &s;piteful. Good morrow, Woodley! Come, Loui&s;a.</P>
<STAGE>(Exeunt Ladies, and the Colonel.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>So&mdash;I am once more left at lei&s;ure for my own reflection. Solitude is &s;aid to be a relief to the unhappy; but thought only &s;erves to double my di&s;tre&s;s. Surely my poverty begins to be appa|rent,
<PB N="10" REF="16">
or Knightly would not write &s;o pre&s;&s;ingly.&mdash;His note &s;urpri&s;es me. <STAGE>(Reads)</STAGE> 
<LETTER>
<P>Dear Woodley, I de&s;ire you will, on receipt of this, let me have the three hundred pieces you lo&s;t to me at our la&s;t Meeting, as I am ju&s;t &s;etting off for Newmarket, and mu&s;t have &s;ome weight of metal to balance the &s;cales on the turf. I &s;hall wait at home for you exactly one hour, by the be&s;t going watch in Eu|rope, and mu&s;t have the ca&s;h by that time, pos.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Yours ever,
T. KNIGHTLY.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</LETTER></P>
<P>The peremptory &s;tile of this billet alarms me! Knightly u&s;ed to be a carele&s;s, liberal fellow; but Mountfort told me ju&s;t now, that he is on the verge of ruin. His &s;tate, however, is to be envied, in com|pari&s;on of mine. He falls alone. No wife, no family, at once to &s;hare and aggravate his wretched|ne&s;s. I'll go this moment and acquit me of his de|mand, by parting with the&s;e toys&mdash; <STAGE>(takes up the ear-rings).</STAGE> How much my Mary's beauty added to their lu&s;tre! Let me fly from the thought.</P>
<STAGE>[Going.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Bromley.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ju&s;t on the wing, my dear friend! How lucky thus to catch you flying, as it were!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>The good fortune is rather mine, Mr. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no; you compliment.&mdash;But where are the dear, the divine Ladies?&mdash;Mayn't I hope to be cheared with one glance from their bright eyes?&mdash;What a beautiful creature is Lady Mary!&mdash;Do you know &s;he wants but little, very little, my dear friend, to be the top of the tree, the very para|gon of fine ta&s;te and <HI>bon ton;</HI> and I think &s;he will very &s;oon acquire that little. My Dame has an ex|cellent hand at touching up the la&s;t poli&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I allow Mrs. Bromley to be perfectly elegant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no; there you are wrong.&mdash;She is pretty, lively, and &s;o forth, but &s;omewhat &s;ub&s;y, you know.&mdash;But Lady Mary, Lady Mary is the thing!&mdash;But what's here? <STAGE>(taking up the ear-rings)</STAGE>&mdash;A new purcha&s;e, I pre&s;ume? They are fine, very fine, indeed! What now may the value be?&mdash;Some thou&s;ands, I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>They did co&s;t a pretty large &s;um, when they were bought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not new, then, I perceive&mdash;but fine, very fine, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Mary don't quite like the fa&s;hion&mdash;the &s;etting, I mean;&mdash;and therefore I &s;hould not be &s;orry to part with them&mdash;and buy others.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>O, that alters the ca&s;e con&s;iderably! Let us &s;ee&mdash;let's &s;ee. Why now, upon examining them clo&s;ely, they appear but middling, very mid|dling, indeed. I don't wonder Lady Mary &s;hould not like them&mdash;no lu&s;tre&mdash;very old fa&s;hion'd&mdash;they'll &s;ell for little or nothing, believe me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>They co&s;t me fifteen hundred pounds, about four years ago.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fifteen hundred pounds!&mdash;You amaze me!&mdash;You mu&s;t have been &s;adly impo&s;ed upon! very &s;adly, indeed, my dear friend! What mon&s;trous cheats the&s;e tradesfolks are!&mdash;Why, the&s;e jewels, now, will not bring above three hundred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's more than the common di&s;pro|portion between buying and &s;elling, I &s;hould think, Mr. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean in the Trade, Mr. Woodley. Among the Trade, diamonds are a drug, a mere drug, indeed: and money is a rare jewel in all trades now, I'll a&s;&s;ure you. A Gentleman, or a friend, per|haps, might give more. Come, for the frolic's &s;ake, I'll turn jeweller my&s;elf, and offer you a cool five
<PB N="12" REF="18">
hundred for them. What &s;ay you? Is it a bargain, Woodley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.</STAGE>
<P>I cannot bear the thought of carrying them abroad to &s;ell!&mdash;Well, if you really think they are worth no more&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, I have over-rated them; but I never compute by pounds, &s;hillings, and pence, when dealing with a friend. Diamonds are, as I told you before, a mere drug; and ca&s;h, ca&s;h, my dear boy, your only valuable commodity. Here, here it is <STAGE>(looking in his pocket-book).</STAGE>&mdash;I have not quite &s;o much about me, I find.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's unlucky <STAGE>(looking at his watch);</STAGE> for I want three hundred of it, this very in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>Does the wind &s;it in that point?&mdash;I'll &s;ee&mdash;I'll &s;ee. O! here is ju&s;t the three hundred, cut and dry, my boy. You &s;hall have the other two this evening at Boodle's. We'll cut a card, or throw a ca&s;t for it, or how you will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;han't go to Boodle's to-night&mdash;nor do I think I &s;hall ever play again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>The knowing-ones are taken in. I would not have given &s;o much for the jewels, if I had thought &s;o.&mdash;What, not play? That's good, very good, indeed! You have a &s;ort of lover's quarrel to the dice, I perceive. But though they have, I confe&s;s, u&s;ed you a little &s;curvily, they'll make you amends &s;ome other time. One lucky hit, you know, may repay all your lo&s;&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>They have &s;o often, and &s;o fatally de|ceived me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you'll tru&s;t them again, for all that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think not. But we &s;hall meet at dinner?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes; I obey the dear, &s;weet Lady Mary's invitation. I &s;hall bring the money with me. Be&s;ides, I recollect, that you and I have a little
<PB N="13" REF="19">
matter of bu&s;ine&s;s to &s;ettle; but it &s;han't break in upon our plea&s;ures, tho'. You &s;hall have no trouble but ju&s;t to &s;et your name. A memorandum is all I want, my boy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have a particular rea&s;on for de&s;iring that you will not mention the tran&s;action of the jewels to my wife, or even to yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Secret&mdash;&s;ecret as the grave, my dear friend&mdash;tru&s;ty as &s;teel, my boy. You may always depend upon hone&s;t Bob Bromley. We &s;hall be with you at five, tho' that's rather early <STAGE>(going).</STAGE>&mdash;Nay, no ceremony.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am going out this moment.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Forward.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have li&s;tened and pryed to good purpo&s;e, I think, and am thoroughly confirmed in my re&s;olution of &s;hifting my quarters, to-morrow morning. Up tents, and away, then! But I cannot help being a little concerned at leaving my ma&s;ter and Lady; becau&s;e I am &s;ure I &s;hall never get &s;o good a place again. All ma&s;ters&mdash;no &s;ervants&mdash;every one did as he liked. It grieves me to think what a hand the re&s;t of the &s;ervants have made of them. There's the lazy Hou&s;ekeeper, the drunken Butler, the cribbing Coachman!&mdash;But what &s;ignifies moralizing! Let me look about me a little, and &s;ee if there be any &s;mall matters lying loo&s;e, that are of no farther u&s;e to my ma&s;ter, and may be of &s;ome to me.&mdash; <STAGE>(Takes up a pair of lace ruffles)</STAGE> The&s;e have been worn, but never wa&s;hed, and he may mi&s;s them. No, that's not probable, as he has at lea&s;t twenty pair more than he knows any thing of&mdash; <STAGE>(puts them in his pocket).</STAGE> This &s;nuff-box, too, is but a bauble, of more curio&s;ity than value: I &s;hall accept of it as a keep-&s;ake&mdash; <STAGE>(pockets it).</STAGE></P>
<PB N="14" REF="20">
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> William, <HI>from the middle door.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the quietne&s;s in the ne&s;t, the birds are flown; and I am glad of it. My apartment &s;mokes a little, to-day. I'll have the tables brought here, and try if the game be recoverable: tho', to be &s;ure, I have but little hopes; for &s;ure there never was any man &s;o unlucky.&mdash;Waters!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>What! is old Square-Toes ruined, too? Egad, I &s;hould be glad of that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(&s;eeing</HI> Forward)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;Why, hey, what are you doing here?&mdash;Waters! I &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only removing a few u&s;ele&s;s things of my ma&s;ter's, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you will certainly remove your|&s;elf; for I know nothing half &s;o u&s;ele&s;s, as a pert, coxcomical, lazy Valet-de-Chambre.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>As your Honour chu&s;es to be alone, I &s;hall retire directly.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Retire! There's a phra&s;e now for a foot|man! But the&s;e puppies all mimic their ma&s;ters, even in their language, and what's wor&s;e, in their vices. I'll an&s;wer for it that fellow now, is as idle, as di&s;&s;ipat|ed, and extravagant, as my nephew him&s;elf. But why do I think of a man who&s;e mi&s;conduct has &s;o totally alienated my affections? Yet he was a &s;weet boy at Eton, and a fine youth at College. His in|di&s;creet marriage has ruined him&mdash;a fine Lady&mdash;a Lady of Quality, for&s;ooth, and without a fortune to &s;upport her vanity. But, no matter now&mdash;I re|nounce them both.&mdash;Waters!&mdash;I wi&s;h Loui&s;a was removed from this &s;cene of folly and extravagance, and &s;afely &s;ettled in the country. There is no other place for a woman to be &s;ecure in.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Waters.</STAGE>
<P>I wi&s;h you would advance, Mr. Slow-boots. I have called you at lea&s;t a dozen times.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>I came the very moment&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, well&mdash;apologies take up time.&mdash;Bring the back-gammon tables here, then go to Coun&s;ellor Belford, and de&s;ire him to come to me, directly.&mdash; <STAGE>(Waters going through the middle door)</STAGE>&mdash;Why don't you go the &s;horte&s;t way?</P>
<STAGE>(pointing to the &s;ide-door.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Honour bid me bring the tables, fir&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of what u&s;e are they, when Belford is not here to play?&mdash; <STAGE>(Waters going)</STAGE>&mdash;No, come back, and fetch the tables, and I'll place the men ju&s;t to &s;hew you how I was gammoned, and I think you'll allow there never was &s;uch luck.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am utterly ignorant of every point of the game, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stupidity in the ab&s;tract! How often have you been in the room, while Belford and I have been playing! Had we been &s;aying or doing any thing we ought not, you would have picked it up fa&s;t enough, I warrant you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No words&mdash;I hate prate&mdash;fly to Mr. Belford's&mdash; <STAGE>[Exit Waters]</STAGE>&mdash;I'll go and &s;hew Jones how it was; for tho' &s;he is my Hou&s;ekeeper, now, &s;he is a Par&s;on's daughter, and mu&s;t under&s;tand back|gammon. I am &s;ure &s;he will be a&s;toni&s;hed at Bel|ford's move.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="16" REF="22">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>continued.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter, at oppo&s;ite doors, Mr.</HI> WOODLEY, <HI>and Mr.</HI> BELFORD.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>HOW truly do I rejoice to &s;ee my good friend Mr. Belford! But may I flat|ter my&s;elf that the honour of this vi&s;it was intended for me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry, my dear Sir, that there &s;hould be a nece&s;&s;ity for di&s;criminating the per&s;on to whom my re&s;pects are paid, in a family I &s;o equal|ly regard, and which was once &s;o happily united.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>If indeed you regard this family, or ever had any friend&s;hip for me&mdash;But I cannot &s;peak.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am already apprized of your difficul|ties, and would &s;pare you the pain of even hinting at them, were it in my power to redre&s;s them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then be a&s;&s;ured it is; for amid&s;t all my di&s;tre&s;&s;es, nothing afflicts me half &s;o much as Sir William's implacable re&s;entment again&s;t Lady Mary and me. If he were but reconciled&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is, in plain Engli&s;h, my young friend, if he could be reconciled to your expen&s;ive mode of living, he ought in honour to a&s;&s;i&s;t in &s;up|porting it. But that, I doubt, will never be brought to pa&s;s, though Sir William is both rich and ge|nerous&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>To all the world, but me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>In this ca&s;e, then, you &s;hould &s;u&s;pect your own conduct, rather than his character.&mdash;But remon&s;trances are u&s;ele&s;s, now; and I promi&s;e to u&s;e my utmo&s;t intere&s;t to bring about a reconciliation.
<PB N="17" REF="23">
But I much fear that we &s;hall not be able to get Lady Mary included in the family-compact; for I know no man more re&s;olute in what he conceives to be right, than Sir William.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>My honour, as well as my love, obliges me to vindicate her; and I here pledge them both, that &s;he is free from blame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am glad to find you &s;till a lover, Mr. Woodley; but I who am but a friend, in this que&s;|tion, can't help thinking, that if Lady Mary had &s;pent more of her time in Dor&s;et&s;hire, and le&s;s at Spa, Paris, and other places of di&s;&s;ipation and ex|travagance, &s;he would have been more entitled to Sir William's e&s;teem, and you would have had le&s;s need of his a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>The fault was mine alone.&mdash;Vain of po&s;|&s;e&s;&s;ing &s;uch a trea&s;ure&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>You childi&s;hly expo&s;ed it to the gaze of fops and foreigners.&mdash;And let me tell you, Mr. Woodley, you are a lucky man, in the&s;e licentious times, to have pre&s;erved &s;uch a gem pure and entire, even at the expence of your other po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ions. But, prithee, why don't you now retreat into the country?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>My wife is quite ignorant of my pre|&s;ent circum&s;tances&mdash;I have not re&s;olution to ac|quaint her with them&mdash;and to propo&s;e quitting London, in this gay &s;ea&s;on, without a&s;&s;igning &s;ome cau&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would, in your &s;ituation, be extremely prudent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot bear the thought of giving her unea&s;ine&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o cruelly prefer the evil to the cure.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WATERS.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>I humbly beg your Honour's pardon for my intru&s;ion, but I have been at your Chambers,
<PB N="18" REF="24">
and at the Temple Coffee-hou&s;e, to look for you. My ma&s;ter is quite impatient to &s;ee you, Sir, and one of Mr. Woodley's &s;ervants told me you were here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;eems to fall out luckily. I will not detain you a moment. Dear Belford, remember what a cau&s;e you have in hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not di&s;tru&s;t my attention to my client, tho' I cannot warrant &s;ucce&s;s to the &s;uit.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Woodley.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot tell your Honour how proud I am to meet you. My good, dear ma&s;ter has been as angry with me for not finding you at home, as if I had committed the greate&s;t of faults; and I would die rather than vex him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know my friend's ha&s;ty temper, per|fectly well; but I al&s;o know that his good-nature is an over-match for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Sir! you don't know how good and generous he is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are mi&s;taken, Waters; I am no &s;tranger to Sir William's benevolence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir, with &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion you are;&mdash;for he takes as much pains to conceal his goodne&s;s, as others do to reveal theirs. He would never for|give me if he knew I mentioned it; but my heart is &s;o glad, I can't help telling your Honour that he apprenticed my elde&s;t boy, la&s;t week, and pays for the &s;chooling of the two younge&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e are noble bounties, I confe&s;s, Waters; but I think your feelings on the occa&s;ion do as much honour to human nature, as the Knight's genero&s;ity;&mdash;for a liberal hand is more frequently to be met with, than a grateful heart.&mdash;But where is Sir William?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>I left him going to take a turn in the garden, and I don't in the lea&s;t doubt but he will come in as cool as a cucumber, tho' when he went
<PB N="19" REF="25">
down &s;tairs he was as angry with me, as if he had never done me any good.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew me the way, and I'll go to him directly.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt thro' the middle door.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>changes to a Dre&s;&s;ing-Room, an elegant Toilet.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Lady</HI> MARY, <HI>and Mrs.</HI> BROMLEY.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(taking up the dre&s;&s;ing plate)</STAGE>
<P>They are pretty, I confe&s;s; but even I think them rather dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What an idea for my dear Lady Mary! Do you know, now, that the equipage of Mrs. Stockwell's toilet, the Broker's wife, co&s;t thirteen hundred pounds?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I remember her at Paris&mdash;an over|dre&s;&s;ed Thing!&mdash;I thought &s;he had been a Jeweller's wife, and looked upon her as a &s;talking &s;hew-gla&s;s, to expo&s;e her hu&s;band's goods for &s;ale. But the poor man, I &s;uppo&s;e, was ruined by her extravagance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, he was <HI>done-up,</HI> very &s;oon after. But the woman had wit in her madne&s;s, however; for &s;he &s;ecreted her paraphernalia, and her chariot has rolled on her per&s;onal fortune, ever &s;ince. Women are much wi&s;er, now-a-days, than they u&s;ed to be.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> WILLIAMS.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Williams.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip's ma&s;querade dre&s;s is ju&s;t come home, Ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me &s;ee! let me &s;ee!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>How beautiful! My dear crea|ture, <Q>You'll look a Godde&s;s, and you'll move a Queen!</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Bromley! I have ju&s;t recollected that I can't go as a Sultana. I have &s;ent my ear-rings to be altered, and the re&s;t of my jewels will make no figure without them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="26">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hire, hire, my Dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't under&s;tand you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a baby, Mrs. Williams! but 'tis a &s;weet baby, we mu&s;t allow. Why, for fifty, or a hundred guineas, at mo&s;t, you may hire as many diamonds as would out-blaze the throne of Dehli.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>A hundred guineas! What a &s;um for one night's vanity! No&mdash;I'll go as a Shepherde&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That wou'd be a di&s;gui&s;e, indeed, in the&s;e days of martial ardour, when our whole Sex have exchanged their old fa&s;hion'd &s;implicity of dre&s;s and manners, for the military air, the &s;mart cockade, and lively regimental.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>But one may be allowed to look inno|cent in ma&s;querade, I hope?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, my little fly one! have I found you out?&mdash;Nothing but a Corydon cou'd have in&s;pired &s;uch an idea.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>All dre&s;&s;es, I fancy, are alike to Mr. Woodley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Woodley! Ridiculous! Why, &s;urely, my dear, you don't think of expo&s;ing your|&s;elf to be the je&s;t of the whole Town, by going <HI>en groupe</HI> with your hu&s;band to a Ma&s;querade!&mdash;Would not the dear, good natured Sir Harry Granger, or even the wi&s;e Colonel Mountfort, make a better Corydon for our &s;weet Shepherde&s;s, think you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>How idly you talk!&mdash;Mountfort is Loui&s;a's Ceci&s;beo, and Sir Harry, I fancy, would be proud to enli&s;t under your banner, in the &s;ame capacity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is wilful blindne&s;s, Lady Mary, for you can't avoid &s;eeing that Sir Harry is your &s;lave. I pity him with all my heart, and w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;h you would do &s;o too. Poor &s;oul, how he doats upon you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="27">
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll make me angry, Mrs. Bromley.&mdash;But, prithee, why mu&s;t I be treated like a picture for a drawing room, not to be hung up without its companion? I want no Corydon, I a&s;&s;ure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, to be &s;ure&mdash;quite lonely and di&s;creet. Come, come, my dear Lady Mary, you were not de&s;igned for a &s;imple Shepherde&s;s:&mdash;the Sultana is your natural character&mdash;born to command, and be adored. But you mu&s;t and &s;hall be fine; for let the men &s;ay what they will of native charms, our diamonds add con&s;iderably to the lu&s;tre of our eyes. What &s;ay you, Mrs. Williams?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Williams.</SPEAKER>
<P>There never was a truer word &s;poken, Ma'am; for though my Lady wants no off|&s;ettings, and looks like an angel in any dre&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>A truce with your flattery, Williams!&mdash;Take away the dre&s;s&mdash;I &s;hall con&s;ider of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Williams.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Nobody's flattery will go down, now, but Mrs. Bromley's, it &s;eems.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould like the Sultana, I confe&s;s; but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can't you gue&s;s? You know I have been &s;tripped at play, and have &s;quandered a great deal of money, this morning. I am &s;orry I bought the&s;e toys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me! how you talk? you that have the fonde&s;t, and the mo&s;t indulgent hu&s;band breathing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>For that very rea&s;on, my dear Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You really talk like a wife of the la&s;t century.&mdash;Here's a fu&s;s, indeed, about a poor hundred guineas! Do you know, now, that I would not have this &s;tory told of you, in any polite circle, for treble the &s;um.&mdash;If it &s;hould take wind, you'd be &s;neered to death with encomiums on your Lady|&s;hip's very uncommon prudence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I &s;hould not care to be thought
<PB N="22" REF="28">
too prudent, neither; &s;o I beg you'll not mention it to any one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may rely on my friend&s;hip.&mdash;And now, my Dear, what jewels would you have?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You can't imagine how much di&s;tre&s;&s;ed I am, upon this trifling &s;ubject. I'm re&s;olved not to a&s;k Mr Woodley for money, to-day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Borrow, then. You may com|mand thou&s;ands, to my knowledge. Sir Harry is as rich as all Duke's Place, and I am &s;ure he would be happy to lay all his trea&s;ures at your feet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Borrow money from Sir Harry Gran|ger!&mdash;You cannot mean it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Sure never mortal was &s;o ea&s;ily taken-in, as my dear Lady Mary! You could not think me &s;erious, I hope.&mdash;Not but I know many wives&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who are a reproach to their Sex, perhaps.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No preaching, if you love me!&mdash;I &s;hall get the jewels for you, on my own credit; for I am re&s;olved that you &s;hall not only be the lovelie&s;t, but the fine&s;t woman, in all that dear, gay, motley A&s;&s;embly, to-night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, my dear Bromley.&mdash;I think the dre&s;s will become me.&mdash;But I owe you a mon&s;trous deal of money, I'm afraid, already.&mdash;How much is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>A trifle, a very trifle, indeed, between &s;uch friends! and I &s;hall be apt to quarrel with you, if ever you mention it again&mdash;let the men &s;ettle it.&mdash;I &s;hall bring the jewels with me at five; 'till then, <HI>adio mia cara.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Bromley comes, I hope?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord! who knows any thing of a Hu&s;band's engagements, my Dear? But there is no doubt of his attending your &s;ummons, on any occa|&s;ion, for my poor Bromley dies for you. You are quite a monopolizer, Lady Mary!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a rattle you are!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="23" REF="29">
SCENE <HI>changes to Sir</HI> WILLIAM<HI>'s Apartment</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> WILLIAM <HI>and Mr.</HI> BELFORD <HI>at Back-gammon.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, I will hear no more of him.&mdash;If he has de&s;troyed his fortune, he &s;hall not de|&s;troy my peace.&mdash; <STAGE>(throws the dice)</STAGE> Cinque ace.&mdash;Come, come, 'tis your throw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is amazing, Sir William, that you can be &s;o anxious about this trifling game, and at the &s;ame time &s;o indifferent about your nephew!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am in earne&s;t about every thing, Mr. Belford; con&s;equently, in my re&s;entment again&s;t my &s;illy nephew, who is a &s;lave to his wife, and a victim to his vanity. Will you take the box, I &s;ay?</P>
<STAGE>(ha&s;tily)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gently, gently, my good Sir William.&mdash;You have put your&s;elf in a pa&s;&s;ion, already.</P>
<STAGE>(ri&s;es)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, 'tis you that have put me in a pa&s;&s;ion.&mdash;I hate <HI>gently,</HI> and all the phlegmatic people in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet you and I have been friends, the&s;e twenty years.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, true, my dear Belford!&mdash;and, perhaps, I am indebted to your <HI>gently,</HI> for our conti|nuing &s;o.&mdash;But don't put my patience to any further trial, at pre&s;ent.&mdash;Sit down, I entreat you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>But one word more, and I have done.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I am patient, but don't harp again on the &s;ame &s;tring&mdash;No more of Mr. Wood|ley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have a noble fortune, Sir William!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, thanks to Providence! more than I have occa&s;ion for my&s;elf, and therefore I con&s;ider the overplus but as a bank for my friends.&mdash;Do you want money, Belford? Name the &s;um, and take it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="30">
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, Sir William, but 'tis not my wants I wi&s;h you to &s;upply, but tho&s;e of your nephew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! at it again? I will not give him a doit&mdash;not a doit, Sir. My fortune &s;hall not be lavi&s;hed to indulge his vanity, or &s;upply his prodigality.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am per&s;uaded he has &s;o thoroughly re|flected upon his pa&s;t folly, that he would make a proper u&s;e of your future kindne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let him alter his conduct, fir&s;t, if he expects I &s;hould alter mine. His repentance may merit my bounty; but my liberality &s;hall not pre|vent his reformation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>But if Mr. Woodley &s;hould be undone, what will become of your niece?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let her &s;hare his fate, as &s;he has done his folly&mdash;&s;he has earned it.&mdash;An extravagant woman, that could not be content to live at one of the fine&s;t Seats in England, but mu&s;t fri&s;k it to Spa and Paris, for&s;ooth, like the re&s;t of the &s;illy Engli&s;h, to &s;quander their money, and be laughed at by Foreigners!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I under&s;tood Mi&s;s Woodley had remain|ed in England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Loui&s;a! I did not &s;peak of her&mdash;&s;he is the be&s;t girl on earth.&mdash;No, no&mdash;&s;he &s;han't &s;uffer for other people's faults. If he has involved her fortune too, I &s;hall take care of her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you intend &s;he &s;hall live with you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, no&mdash;I'll have no mi&s;tre&s;s in my hou&s;e, but old Jones. I would not di&s;place her for a Duche&s;s&mdash;it would break the poor woman's heart.&mdash;But I &s;hall take proper care of Loui&s;a.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I wi&s;h &s;he was well married, out of the way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>But now give me leave, Sir William&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Neither now, nor then, Mr. Belford. The matter is all &s;ettled in my mind, and the game gone quite out of my head. I'll &s;end for Loui&s;a, directly, and talk this matter over with her.&mdash;Waters! <HI>(enter Waters)</HI> Step in to Mr. Woodley's, and de&s;ire my niece to come to me immediately.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit Waters.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry I have been &s;o un&s;ucce&s;sful in my &s;uit, Sir William, and wi&s;h you a good-day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are not angry with me, I hope, Belford?&mdash;I am as &s;orry for my nephew's indi&s;cre|tion as you or any one can be.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you are, you will certainly a&s;&s;i&s;t him. <HI>(a&s;ide)</HI> But I know it mu&s;t be all done in your own way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dine with me, and we'll play out our party, after dinner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart, but I &s;hall be too many for you, as u&s;ual.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I had not the greate&s;t regard ima|ginable for my old friend, I &s;hould hate him abominably, for always beating me at backgammon. But let me con&s;ider, now&mdash;She has ten thou&s;and pounds of her own. I will give her as much more, at pre&s;ent, and my whole e&s;tate, after my death.&mdash;No, no,&mdash;that won't be acting ju&s;tly&mdash;Woodley may have children&mdash;They have not offended me, though their father has;&mdash;and if they &s;hould be half &s;o plea&s;ant as he was when he was a child, I &s;hould love them dearly, as I once did him. But I mu&s;t &s;trive to forget all that bu&s;ine&s;s, now.&mdash;Here comes Loui&s;a.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> MARY, <HI>who keeps at a di&s;tance, without Sir</HI> WILLIAM<HI>'s looking at her.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, child; you know, I &s;uppo&s;e, that my hopeful nephew is totally ruined&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you come nearer? I wouldn't have all the hou&s;e hear me.&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;he advances)</STAGE> My nephew, I tell you, is ruined.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I could not have imagined, Sir, when you did me the honour of &s;ending for me, that you meant to alarm or in&s;ult me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(looking at her)</STAGE>
<P>I &s;end for you! I in|&s;ult you!&mdash;That blundering Waters!&mdash;No, Madam, you are the la&s;t per&s;on in the world, except your hu&s;band, that I &s;hould think of &s;ending for.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>The re&s;pect I have for you, Sir, as Mr. Woodley's relation, mu&s;t make it extremely painful to me to know that I am &s;o di&s;agreeable to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;pect for me, Madam! I don't de|&s;ire your re&s;pect, nor de&s;erve your re&s;pect.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> If &s;he talks in this way, &s;he'll &s;tagger my re&s;olution.&mdash;I wanted to &s;peak with my niece, Madam, and my blundering &s;ervant&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has brought you one that is proud of that title, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have a title of your own, Madam.&mdash;I hate titles&mdash;and one rea&s;on why I never married, was becau&s;e I would not have my wife called my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee, Sir William, that you are not inclined&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>To conver&s;e with <HI>Ladies,</HI> Madam.&mdash;I would &s;peak with Loui&s;a, upon bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall no longer obtrude on you, Sir; but before I go, mu&s;t reque&s;t you'll explain what you meant by &s;aying that Mr. Woodley was ruined.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>She knows nothing of the matter, I find, and I cannot bear to &s;hock her.&mdash;I think, Madam, you ought to under&s;tand that matter as well as I.&mdash;Ruined!&mdash;Why, 'tis a common phra&s;e, at pre&s;ent, Madam.&mdash;Dukes, Lords, and Commons, nay, the whole Nation, are ruined, Ma|dam&mdash;'tis
<PB N="27" REF="33">
quite the <HI>Ton;</HI> and I &s;uppo&s;e that neither Mr. Woodley nor you would chu&s;e to be out of the fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, Sir, you'll allow that Mr. Woodley's fortune, and my rank, entitles us&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be ruined in good company, Ma|dam.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> She has touched the right key now. I'm no more afraid of her. Had &s;he fallen a-crying, I might have been ruined too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry to find, Sir, that your pre|judices again&s;t Mr. Woodley and me are &s;o &s;trong, that it would be in vain for us to attempt a ju&s;tifi|cation of our conduct.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Quite &s;o, indeed, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall therefore take my leave, Sir.</P>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>You have mine, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I &s;end Mi&s;s Woodley to you, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Madam, no; I'll &s;end for her when I am a little more compo&s;ed. Your &s;ervant&mdash;your &s;ervant, Madam.&mdash; <STAGE>[Exit Lady Mary]</STAGE>&mdash;Waters!&mdash;What a martyrdom has this fellow expo&s;ed me to!&mdash;Waters!&mdash; <STAGE>(enter Waters)</STAGE>&mdash;Thou eternal blockhead, dolt, dunderhead&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does your Honour &s;peak to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; to the door; to the window; to this table&mdash;Matter it&s;elf has more intelligence than thou.</P>
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would your Honour plea&s;e to have dinner &s;erved? It is quite ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let it wait.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Belford is below, Sir,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I'll go then. What a provoking blunder!</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="28" REF="34">
SCENE, <HI>Mr.</HI> WOODLEY's <HI>Dre&s;&s;ing-Room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Mr.</HI> WOODLEY <HI>alone.</HI></STAGE>
<P>If Belford &s;hould &s;ucceed with my uncle, all may yet be well. Something mu&s;t be done, and quickly too. I can no longer endure the agony of endea|vouring to impo&s;e upon the world, and my&s;elf, by per&s;onating a borrowed character. But here &s;he comes, who innocently adds to all my &s;ufferings, and tips the darts of poverty with angui&s;h!</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> Mary.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! my dear Woodley! &s;uch a trial ordeal as I have undergone! I declare I would ra|ther be buried alive, in Dor&s;et&s;hire, than endure &s;uch another <HI>t&ecirc;te-&agrave;-t&ecirc;te.</HI> He has done every thing, but beat me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't comprehend you&mdash;Whom do you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, that's downright perver&s;ene&s;s; for I am certain there is not &s;uch another creature upon earth, as your precious Uncle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope you have not quarrelled with him, Lady Mary?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, truly; he has &s;pared me that trouble, by quarrelling with me, mo&s;t outrageou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>Then all my hopes in Belford are at an end. I am very &s;orry you happened to come in his way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm &s;ure &s;o am I, Mr. Woodley. The interview was not of my &s;eeking; and though I was as mild as a lamb, he was as rude as a bear. The deuce take his blundering &s;ervant for bringing me into &s;uch a &s;crape!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould hope that your regard for me would have prevented&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o it did, I a&s;&s;ure you; for I did not laugh, tho' he &s;aid &s;omething &s;o ridiculous,
<PB N="29" REF="35">
about your being ruined, the Nation being ruined, and all the world being ruined, that I had much ado to keep my countenance. However, I behaved very decently all the while, and even conde&s;cended to en|treat that he would give you leave to ju&s;tify your conduct to him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And did my dear Mary obtain his per|mi&s;&s;ion?</P>
<STAGE>(with eagerne&s;s.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your earne&s;tne&s;s &s;tartles me, Mr. Woodley. Of what con&s;equence can the old-fa&s;hion|ed opinion of an ob&s;tinate Don Choleric, who hates us both, be of to us? I wi&s;h he would endow an Ho&s;pital with his fortune, that our &s;olicitude to plea&s;e might end with our expectations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mine &s;hould not, I a&s;&s;ure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>That mu&s;t be as you plea&s;e, Mr. Woodley; but I declare, that from this hour&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Make no ra&s;h vows, Madam. You know not how much you have been, or may be, in|debted to Sir William.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I indebted to him! No, Mr. Woodley, that I po&s;itively deny.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr. and Mrs.</HI> Bromley.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(entering.)</STAGE>
<P>And &s;o do I, with both my hands, and all my heart; for be the que&s;tion in Law, Phy&s;ic, or Divinity, I'll pawn my life on't, that Lady Mary is right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am much obliged to you for your good opinion, Mr. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I wager on Mr. Woodley's &s;ide, were it only to keep up the argument. The que&s;tion, then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, the que&s;tion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to Mrs. Bromley.)</STAGE>
<P>There are &s;ecrets in all families, you know, my dear Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And it is always prudent to keep them &s;o, Lady Mary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="36">
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very good, very good, indeed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Curio&s;ity, thank heaven, is not one of my failings. 'Tis ever a mark both of igno|rance and ill-breeding. I am a&s;toni&s;hed how any one can be infected with &s;uch an impertinent weakne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, my Dame is quite above all &s;illy curio&s;ity&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> The verie&s;t eaves-dropper that ever exi&s;ted. She'll not re&s;t 'till &s;he has got the whole &s;tory, and I &s;hall have it the moment we get home.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Mrs.</HI> Bromley <HI>&s;hews a Box of Jewels to Lady</HI> Mary.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>They are quite charming, indeed! I &s;hall outblaze the Queen of Diamonds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What jewels are the&s;e? I hope you have not bought them, Lady Mary!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You hope I have not bought them&mdash;What an odd &s;peech, Mr. Woodley! No; I have only borrowed them, and will lend you part, if you'll go <HI>en Turc.</HI> I can &s;pare enough to ornament his turban, can't I, Bromley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely you don't per&s;i&s;t in making a family party, Lady Mary?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to Mr. Woodley.)</STAGE>
<P>You &s;hall have the&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prithee, don't teize me, Lady Mary&mdash;I &s;hall not go to the Ma&s;querade.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>Don't teize me! Something extraordinary mu&s;t have di&s;turbed him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll have a charming &s;queeze at your rout, Lady Mary! Not a vacant chair to be found in the whole hou&s;e, I warrant you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You flatter me. No; I believe there will hardly be any body. Do you know that I have had a hundred and ninety-one excu&s;es within the&s;e two days?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, but you'll have nine hundred
<PB N="31" REF="37">
and ninety people, for all that. I hope Lady Sitfa&s;t won't come! That woman never orders her carriage till near one, tho' &s;he plagues the &s;ervant to call it up, every five minutes after eleven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there's that poor, drooping Mrs. Henpeck, who always lo&s;es, and &s;its moaning over her lo&s;&s;es, and playing the after-game, 'till the &s;er|vants are obliged to put her out along with the candles.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Forward.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more excu&s;es, I hope?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dinner is &s;erved, plea&s;e your Lady&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is Sir Harry Granger come?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, no; he has no longer the <HI>entr&eacute;e</HI> here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm heartily &s;orry for it. No man tem|pers a &s;allad like Sir Harry. He is a perfect com|pendium of the whole art of cookery, and has more good receipts in his pocket-book, than ever were publi&s;hed by the celebrated Hannah Gla&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t excellent qualifications for a man of fa&s;hion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, very true, indeed! Eating is the rage, the high ton, at pre&s;ent, and indeed is one of the mo&s;t refined of our modern &s;tudies.&mdash;Will your Lady&s;hip permit me the tran&s;cendant honour of your fair hand?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I attend Mrs. Bromley.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE SECOND ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="32" REF="38">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE, <HI>a Dining-Parlour.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> WILLIAM <HI>and Mr.</HI> BELFORD <HI>at a Table, with a Bottle and Gla&s;&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I AM no drinking man my&s;elf, Belford; but yet I do not approve of this water &s;y&s;tem of yours. It keeps the &s;pirits too low&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;ay or do any thing mad or fooli&s;h, I grant it may. But if water does not rai&s;e, it never depre&s;&s;es the &s;pirits. Can you &s;ay as much for your generous wine?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I won't di&s;pute with you, becau&s;e I hate argument; and as you are an hone&s;t fellow, I can venture to take my gla&s;s chearfully in your company, tho' you don't partake of my liquor. But I'd give &s;omething, ay, more than I'll mention, that you'd &s;hare only one pint of claret with me, now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have made no vows, Sir William; and to humour a friend can ea&s;ily di&s;pen&s;e with rules of my own making: So here's your fair niece, Loui&s;a Woodley, in a bumper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, thank you, my good friend! She is a mo&s;t excellent girl, and I like to have her toa&s;ted by &s;uch a man as you. I wi&s;h &s;he was well &s;ettled, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>There can be no doubt of her marrying to advantage. She is a fine young woman, with a fine fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o may be &s;acrificed to &s;ome fine young man, that may &s;pend her fortune in finery, as her hopeful brother has done, and leave her a beg|gar.
<PB N="33" REF="39">
No, no,&mdash;I'll prevent that&mdash;I have thought of a match for her&mdash;Fill your gla&s;s, Belford!&mdash;a prudent, &s;ober, &s;en&s;ible man.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I wi&s;h he'd take the hint.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rare qualities, indeed, for a young man of fa&s;hion to po&s;&s;e&s;s, in the&s;e days, Sir Wil|liam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who told you that he was a <HI>young man of fa&s;hion?</HI> Why, Sir, there have been no <HI>men</HI> born, at lea&s;t, for the&s;e la&s;t thirty years&mdash;all monkies and macaronies. No Hearts of Oak, now, Belford,&mdash;all dwindled, dwindled into a&s;pens!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;arca&s;m is rather too general, my good friend. Courage is the birth-right of an Engli&s;hman, and while one acre of our &s;oil remains, both the Oak and the Laurel will thrive on it.&mdash;We mu&s;t not prejudge the ri&s;ing generation; and I have not the lea&s;t doubt but your niece will make a very proper choice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>A choice! I hope &s;he has been better educated, than to have a choice, Sir. I was not con&s;ulted in her brother's match, and you &s;ee the con&s;equence.&mdash;I &s;hall di&s;po&s;e of Loui&s;a in my own way.&mdash;I have a hu&s;band now in my eye for her, Belford.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whoever obtains Mi&s;s Woodley, will, I dare &s;ay, be a very happy man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stick to that, my dear Belford.&mdash;Yes, yes, whoever marries Loui&s;a will be a very happy man, and I am extremely glad you think &s;o.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I wi&s;h he'd come to the point.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know, Sir William, that I have long been acquainted with Mi&s;s Woodley's merit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>You charm me, my dear Belford. I am glad you know her worth, and you will therefore cheri&s;h it.&mdash;She is mild and timid&mdash;but you'll be kind and gentle to her, even for my &s;ake, my good old friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="40">
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Kind and gentle to her!</HI> and your <HI>good old friend!</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, are not you my friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t certainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then why all this reiteration? If you marry Loui&s;a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I marry her, Sir William!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir&mdash;Did you not, this moment, allow that who ever married her, would be a very happy man? And I &s;uppo&s;e, you can have no po&s;&s;ible objection to being a very happy man, Mr. Belford?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, the &s;tronge&s;t in the world, if my happine&s;s is to be purcha&s;ed at the expence of another's mi&s;ery.&mdash;But I am wrong for being &s;erious, when I am certain you do but je&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the fir&s;t place, Sir, I never &s;aid any thing in je&s;t, &s;ince I was born.&mdash;And, &s;econdly, Sir, I never was more in earne&s;t, in the whole cour&s;e of my life. I therefore reque&s;t from you a &s;erious an&s;wer.&mdash;Je&s;t, indeed! No, truly, Coun&s;ellor, I am no joker.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, then, Sir, I &s;hould think my&s;elf highly honoured&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha, p&s;ha, p&s;ha&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Patience, my good friend&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir&mdash;I will have no patience with your non&s;en&s;ical compliments&mdash;none of your ho|nours, I &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>In a word, then, Sir William, the di&s;parity of years between forty-eight and eigh|teen&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is ju&s;t nothing at all.&mdash;What need you tell her you are forty-eight?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>There will be no occa&s;ion, I grant you&mdash;Self-evident propo&s;itions need no proof.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ye, Belford, you fatigue me to death with your logic and &s;ophi&s;try.&mdash;The point
<PB N="35" REF="41">
may be reduced to two words,&mdash;Will you marry my niece, or no?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is a match &s;o infinitely beyond my preten&s;ions, Sir William&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope I may be allowed the be&s;t judge in that matter, Mr. Belford.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means, Sir William, your partial kindne&s;s towards me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is almo&s;t worn out, by your tire&s;ome, fal&s;e mode&s;ty;&mdash;and, if I thought I &s;hould have as much plague with Loui&s;a, as I have had with you, I'd renounce my project, and leave her to die an old maid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>The propo&s;al is &s;o highly favourable to me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you con&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Were I certain that Mi&s;s Woodley's inclinations&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I told you, before, that I could di&s;|po&s;e of them as I plea&s;ed; &s;o that if you have no other objection, I &s;hall carry my point, and &s;ettle one of my family to my entire &s;atisfaction, at la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is impo&s;&s;ible that I can have any objection, if &s;he has none.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your hand then, my dear Belford&mdash;'Tis a match.&mdash;Order your clerks to &s;et about the writings directly.&mdash;Your e&s;tate lies in Stafford&s;hire, I think.&mdash;You know I add ten thou&s;and to her fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;urely, my dear Sir William, Mi&s;s Woodley ought to be made acquainted&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, has &s;he not been acquainted with you ever &s;ince &s;he was born? If I mi&s;take not, you were pre&s;ent at her chri&s;tening.&mdash;The wedding &s;hall be next week&mdash;The &s;ooner my dear girl is happily &s;ettled, the better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your kindne&s;s overwhelms me&mdash;but &s;till, Mi&s;s Woodley&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="36" REF="42">
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall be made acquainted with her happine&s;s, this evening. I leave all the articles of &s;ettlement to your own honour.&mdash;I know you'll make a proper provi&s;ion for my niece, becau&s;e it is po&s;|&s;ible you may die before her&mdash;but no pin-money, I charge you&mdash;'Tis but a prelude to alimony, believe me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall endeavour to acquit my&s;elf as &s;uch a generous confidence de&s;erves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hurry, hurry your clerks, and bring this happy event to a &s;peedy conclu&s;ion, my dear nephew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have the &s;tronge&s;t motives to enforce their diligence, as well as the highe&s;t &s;en&s;e of my obligations to your friend&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;peeches&mdash;ha&s;ten the bu&s;ine&s;s, and adieu.&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Belford.]</STAGE>&mdash;I'll &s;peak to Jones, direct|ly, to prepare for the wedding-dinner. She can't bear to be hurried; and I'd have every thing mag|nificent on that day, which I &s;hall deem the happie&s;t of my whole life; becau&s;e it will be the fir&s;t time I could ever get any of my family to know their own intere&s;t, and act as I would have them.</P>
<STAGE>(going off)</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Loui&s;a.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very glad to &s;ee you, my dear child.&mdash;And now what have you to &s;ay to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was informed, Sir, by my &s;i&s;ter, that you de&s;ired to &s;peak with me, and I am therefore come to receive your commands.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my dear, it will neither be que&s;|tions nor commands, but cro&s;s-purpo&s;es, if you keep at &s;uch a di&s;tance as will make it impo&s;&s;ible we &s;hould hear one another. Come nearer, I &s;ay&mdash;What are you afraid of?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(advancing.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, &s;o&mdash;that will do.&mdash;And now, my dear child, you can't imagine what a heavenly tem|per
<PB N="37" REF="43">
I am in, and what favourable di&s;po&s;itions I have towards you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very happy, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>So you'll &s;ay, my dear, when you know all. But you mu&s;t de&s;erve my kindne&s;s, by your frankne&s;s;&mdash;therefore, fir&s;t tell me, whether you have any particular objection to matrimony?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is a &s;ubject, Sir, that I have never much thought upon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's &s;ingular, now; for I am told that the girls of the&s;e days think of nothing el&s;e. But, luckily, there is no occa&s;ion for your con&s;idering about the matter, as you have &s;uch a friend as I am to con&s;ider for you, child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o I &s;hall make your mind ea&s;y at once, by letting you know that I have provided a hu&s;band for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Now, Heaven forbid!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;uch a one as is not to be met with every day, I a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;a man after my own heart&mdash;has not a fault, Loui&s;a, but that he is a water-drinker. But I won't anticipate, by telling you his name. He &s;hall &s;urpri&s;e you with it him|&s;elf.&mdash;Why, hey!&mdash;what's the matter now? You don't &s;eem at all overjoyed!&mdash;You are not hankering after a title, I hope; for, believe me, niece, if there be either happine&s;s or virtue left in the pre&s;ent world, they are only to be met with in the middle ranks of life. What makes you tremble &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are not unacquainted with my ti|midity, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, I under&s;tand the timidity of your whole &s;ex&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Doves before mar|riage, and Kites after.&mdash;You'll &s;oon get the bet|ter of your timidity, I'll an&s;wer for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I am certain, Sir, that 'tis your wi&s;h to make me happy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="44">
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are right, my dear; but it mu&s;t be my own way. Your brother's want of re&s;pect to my opinion, you &s;ee, has been his ruin, child. Don't attempt to copy him, Loui&s;a.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you would but conde&s;cend to hear me, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, child, I know every thing already, that you would wi&s;h to &s;ay. Your obligations to me, and your mode&s;ty, and your timidity, and your &s;ettlement, and all that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir, I have not a thought about a &s;ettlement&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, every thing &s;hall be taken care of, except a provi&s;ion for a &s;eparate mainte|nance. I bar that; for if you can't live happily with &s;uch a hu&s;band as I have cho&s;en for you, I &s;hould think you de&s;erved to &s;tarve, tho' you were my niece a thou&s;and times.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my dear uncle&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my dear niece, don't in&s;i&s;t upon it; for a woman who thinks of &s;eparation at the moment of her union, does not intend to abide by her hu&s;band, as &s;he ought to do, 'till death do them part.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I neither think of union nor &s;eparation, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mode&s;t and virtuous that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me but one word, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Enough's &s;aid, enough's &s;aid, my dear. Here, take this bill, to provide for your dre&s;s. I'd have every thing hand&s;ome. The ladies are great belles in Stafford&s;hire; and I'd have my niece make as good an appearnace as any <HI>private gentlewoman</HI> among them. Why don't you take the bill? 'Tis for five hundred pounds, and I hope you think that &s;ufficient.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have no &s;ort of occa&s;ion for it, Sir; and if you would but indulge me with a moment's conver&s;ation&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="45">
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha, p&s;ha, p&s;ha,&mdash;I hate all this af|fected delicacy. Take money from the old man whenever you can get it. Ha&s;ten your milliners and mantua-makers, and get all your matters ready by this day &s;e'nnight, for I won't have the wedding de|ferred an hour longer. Delays are ever dangerous.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit, throwing the bill on the table.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, in the name of wonder, can this dear, kind, cruel uncle of mine intend for me? I almo&s;t doubt whether I wake or not. Married in a week, to a man perhaps I never &s;aw! No, that's impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;he is too good to think of &s;uch an union. Po&s;&s;ibly Mountfort may have applied for his con&s;ent, before he a&s;ked mine!&mdash;Too fond a hope, I fear.&mdash;I wi&s;h I could &s;ee Coun&s;ellor Belford; my uncle keeps no &s;ecret from him, and he is a friend to all our fa|mily. I'll write to him to come to me in&s;tantly.</P>
<STAGE>(fits down to the table.)</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> Belford, <HI>without &s;eeing</HI> Loui&s;a.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot proceed on this bu&s;ine&s;s, in earne&s;t, till Sir William has had &s;ome conference with his niece. It is po&s;&s;ible &s;he may di&s;like the match, or perhaps be otherwi&s;e engaged&mdash;and then I &s;hould become the &s;tanding je&s;t of all my brother Benchers. I mu&s;t &s;peak to Sir William again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>My good Mr. Belford, I never was &s;o glad to &s;ee you in my whole life. I have been this moment writing to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>You make me the happie&s;t of mortals, Madam.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide</STAGE> This Brief opens well! I need not be much afraid of being laughed at now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is &s;omething &s;o particular&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide</STAGE> I know not how to mention it&mdash;Mr. Belford, my good uncle has&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I find completed his kindne&s;s, and ac|quainted you, Madam&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="46">
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, but as you &s;hare his confidence, I mu&s;t entreat that you'll inform me&mdash; <STAGE>(be&s;itates)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> Her mode&s;ty di&s;tre&s;&s;es me va&s;tly; but I like her the better for it! I wi&s;h I had a &s;peech ready.&mdash;Did not Sir William, Madam, &s;ay any thing of matrimony to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You can't imagine, Sir, how he has &s;ur|pri&s;ed and terrified me, by talking of my being to be married in a week.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>You might be &s;urpri&s;ed, to be &s;ure, Ma|dam; but I don't &s;ee any occa&s;ion for your being terrified, any more than for &s;uch a violent hurry. The writings can't be properly engro&s;&s;ed in that time. The Law &s;eldom keeps pace with a Lover's wi&s;hes;&mdash;and however impatient I may be to expedite this bu&s;ine&s;s, you &s;hall not be hurried, fair Lady, but be at liberty to name your own day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hall be Doom&s;day, then&mdash;However, I thank you, Sir, for allowing me even a reprieve.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> Hey-dey! Where &s;its the wind now?&mdash;You have no ab&s;olute aver&s;ion to marriage, I hope, Mi&s;s Woodley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I de&s;pi&s;e affectation, Sir, and am above di&s;gui&s;e, with an old friend like you:&mdash;I have no aver&s;ion to marriage, when I can be&s;tow my hand with my heart;&mdash;but I would rather die, than be &s;a|crificed to a frightful fordid wretch, who has tre|panned my uncle out of his con&s;ent, becau&s;e he de|&s;paired of mine, and takes me merely as an appen|dage to my fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> How lucky was my coming back!&mdash;But why &s;hould you &s;uppo&s;e, Madam, that your uncle would <HI>&s;acrifice you to a frightful &s;ordid wretch?</HI> Your intended hu&s;band is a very different kind of man, I'll a&s;&s;ure you, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let him be what he will, Sir, I &s;hall de|te&s;t him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never thought, Mi&s;s Woodley, that my conduct or character had in any in&s;tance merit|ed your dete&s;tation, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dete&s;t you, Mr. Belford! No, that's impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;But how are you concerned in the mat|ter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not much, at pre&s;ent, Madam;&mdash;for I &s;corn to take advantage of your uncle's engagements, unle&s;s ratified by your con&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Mr. Belford!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, never whimper about it. I own, I &s;u&s;pected, from the fir&s;t, that it was rather too good news to be true:&mdash;but don't make your&s;elf unhappy, Mi&s;s Woodley; for I would rather live and die a batchelor, than marry the fine&s;t woman in England, as is now the ca&s;e <STAGE>(bowing),</STAGE> who was not equally ready <HI>to have and to hold.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous, worthy man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not more generous than prudent, Ma|dam, on this occa&s;ion. But, as I hope I have now de&s;erved your confidence, Mi&s;s Woodley, tell me then, if you have any particular attachment, and I &s;hall endeavour to &s;erve you with Sir William;&mdash;though I know I &s;hall, for a time, &s;tand in the light of a culprit before him, by declining the honour he intended me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You overpower me with obligations, Mr. Belford.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;peeches, my dear Madam. If I was not &s;ufficiently gratified by the honour of the act, no acknowledgements could make me amends for the di&s;appointment; &s;o frankly name the hap|py man who is to rai&s;e my envy, and compleat your happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Though I think that a well-placed and mutual affection need not rai&s;e a blu&s;h upon the cha&s;te&s;t cheek, yet mine will glow when I name Co|lonel Mountfort.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="48">
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel Mountfort! I'm &s;orry for it&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e he's a very pretty fellow, Ma|dam, and for that rea&s;on may fall within your un|cle's chapter of coxcombs, and prevent his con&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I &s;hall never give mine to marry any man el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's &s;omewhat in the Knight's own &s;tile, Mi&s;s Woodley. But I heartily wi&s;h you &s;uc|ce&s;s, and &s;hall &s;hew my&s;elf a warmer Friend than a Lover, by u&s;ing my be&s;t pleadings in my rival's &s;uit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Accept my warme&s;t thanks, my good old friend.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay,&mdash;I knew &s;he would always think of me as her <HI>old</HI> friend.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>changes to Mr.</HI> WOODLEY's. <HI>A Dining-Room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Mr.</HI> WOODLEY <HI>and Mr.</HI> BROMLEY <HI>at a Table, with a Dice-Box.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll play no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Bromley.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be &s;ure, my dear friend, luck has run confoundedly again&s;t you; but I never &s;aw you give out for &s;uch a trifling lo&s;s, before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seven hundred pounds is no trifle, Mr. Bromley!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Bromley.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A trifle, indeed, to a per&s;on of your immen&s;e fortune!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have made a fal&s;e e&s;timate of my circum&s;tances. I am rather a di&s;tre&s;&s;ed man, at pre&s;ent, Mr. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Bromley.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> Are you &s;o? Then 'tis time for me to take care of my&s;elf.&mdash;You &s;urpri&s;e me va&s;tly! Di&s;tre&s;&s;ed did you &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="43" REF="49">
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hate to repeat it; but 'tis &s;o true, that I had &s;ome thoughts of applying to your friend|&s;hip, to extricate me out of my pre&s;ent difficulties, Mr. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Command me, command me, my dear Woodley! Every thing that poor Bob Brom|ley has in the world&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> except his money,&mdash;is at your &s;ervice.&mdash;But let us clear as we go&mdash;&s;ettle our little matters fir&s;t&mdash;ju&s;t &s;et your name to this paper&mdash;or will you take another throw, my friend, and let it be double or quit?</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Colonel</HI> MOUNTFORT.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>For &s;hame, Woodley!&mdash;at hazard in your own hou&s;e! I thought you had enough of that at Clubs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Play among friends is wrong, very wrong, I confe&s;s, Colonel; but one can't be always grave and wi&s;e.&mdash;Come, my dear Woodley, let us make an end of our bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;the pen, or the box, my dear boy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>De&s;perate &s;ituations require de&s;perate remedies.&mdash;Give me the box&mdash; <STAGE>(they throw)</STAGE> Damn the dice!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis double, now, you know, my unlucky friend; which makes upon the whole ex|actly the &s;um of &s;even thou&s;and three hundred and fifty-four pounds, including the dear Lady Mary's trifling debt to Mrs. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I have brought a bond with me, and when I have filled up the blanks, if you plea&s;e we'll perfect it in the next room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Sure ne|ver man was &s;o completely unfortunate! Never, by Heaven, will I touch a die again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I give you joy of your lo&s;&s;es; for I
<PB N="44" REF="50">
know you are too much a man of honour to break your vow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Game&s;ters, like lovers, you know, Colonel&mdash;And after all, now, this is but matter of form between friends and men of honour, like you and me.&mdash;Don't you think &s;o, Colonel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>I con&s;ider all compul&s;ive obligations be|tween men as a di&s;grace to human nature. But while there are &s;uch things as knaves in the world, Mr. Bromley, we mu&s;t &s;ubmit to the mean &s;ecurities of bars and bonds. But between men of honour, as you &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly, my dear Sir, men of ho|nour are&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Too often the dupes of knaves, Mr. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>I don't like him.&mdash;We'll talk over the affair you hinted at in the next room. Command me, on all occa&s;ions&mdash;ever&mdash;ever at your &s;ervice. But I mu&s;t attend the ladies. The ladies and the coffee are powerful attractions to me. You'll follow me, I pre&s;ume, Colonel?</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, with plea&s;ure, through my whole re|giment, with a drum at your heels. I am per&s;uaded, Woodley, that fellow is a knave, and I wi&s;h you would exclude both him and his flaunting wife from your's and Lady Mary's &s;ociety. I can't con|ceive why you are &s;o partial to them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>The great civilities we received from them, at Spa, fir&s;t attached my wife to Mrs. Brom|ley, who was there in the fir&s;t &s;ets, and even in Lon|don, where people are more nice. She keeps very good company, I a&s;&s;ure you, Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll pardon me, Woodley!&mdash;She is &s;eldom &s;een in public but with &s;ome damaged Dowager of Quality, who would be excluded from &s;ociety if her title did not &s;erve as a herald to make way for her Lady&s;hip.&mdash;But enough of them! I am come to &s;peak to you on a much more intere&s;ting &s;ubject,
<PB N="45" REF="51">
and to prove&mdash;what, however, I cannot doubt&mdash;your friend&s;hip for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be a&s;&s;ured, my dear Mountfort&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;o&mdash;you need not make profe&s;&s;ions;&mdash;therefore, with the frankne&s;s of a &s;oldier, I venture to a&s;k the highe&s;t proof of your regard, by con&s;ent|ing to make the fair Loui&s;a mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;i&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;eem to he&s;itate, Mr. Woodley! My fortune is&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>As unexceptionable as your character, Colonel; and as I truly love Loui&s;a, and &s;hould rejoice in her happine&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You con&s;ent to mine. Is it &s;o, my friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not how to an&s;wer you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You alarm me extremely, Mr. Woodley! For heaven's &s;ake, &s;peak out!&mdash;What can be your objections?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>None in the world, to you; but cir|cum&s;tanced as I am at pre&s;ent, it would involve me in the greate&s;t difficulties, to be called upon &s;o &s;ud|denly for ten thou&s;and pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;hall not be the ca&s;e, Woodley. I &s;hould think even Loui&s;a too dearly purcha&s;ed, at the expence of di&s;tre&s;&s;ing you. When I a&s;ked for your &s;i&s;ter's hand, I did not demand her pur&s;e; nor &s;hall I accept the one, 'till I have &s;igned a relea&s;e for the other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mountfort, that mu&s;t not, &s;hall not be! I never will accept of &s;uch a &s;acrifice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark-ye, Woodley! A &s;oldier's character &s;hould be uniform; and if there could be one who was not liberal, I &s;hould &s;u&s;pect his courage to be of the mere animal kind. My fortune is &s;ufficiently ample; and I would as &s;oon mount my charger, cry &s;tand and deliver, as take money I don't want, from a friend who does.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your genero&s;ity, Colonel&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="46" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is of too &s;elfi&s;h a nature to merit prai&s;e; for I feel here <STAGE>(laying his hand to his heart)</STAGE> that the true luxury of fortune lies more in giving, than in &s;pending.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will not le&s;&s;en it, by offering thanks. But have you opened your trenches before the Knight of the Ca&s;tle yet? <STAGE>(pointing to the middle door)</STAGE> He u&s;ed to &s;peak well of you, and his opinion is of &s;ome con&s;equence in this bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;entiments are even with the good old Knight's, I a&s;&s;ure you. I e&s;teem his good qualities, and do not di&s;like even his foibles, as they are truly natural and un&s;ophi&s;ticate. But there, perhaps, you may &s;ee me play the u&s;urer, like any Jew. He may double or treble Loui&s;a's fortune, without the lea&s;t impediment from any &s;cruple or mode&s;ty of mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>When do you purpo&s;e to make the e&s;&s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>As &s;oon as po&s;&s;ible; for 'till I have paid the proper re&s;pect due to him, I do not think my&s;elf entitled to throw my&s;elf at Loui&s;a's feet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>May &s;ucce&s;s attend you, my generous friend!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie, Woodley&mdash;no more of that!&mdash;But adieu.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;everally.</STAGE>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE THIRD ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB REF="53">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE, <HI>Lady</HI> MARY<HI>'s Dre&s;&s;ing-Room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Lady</HI> MARY <HI>and Mrs.</HI> BROMLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>AND &s;o that was all?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every word, I a&s;&s;ure you. But we &s;hall &s;oon make it up, for ours are but lovers' quarrels.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovers! talk of love after four years marriage! Believe me, Lady Mary, 'tis all a farce.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my dear Mrs. Bromley, I cannot give you credit again&s;t the feelings of my own heart. I love Mr. Woodley, and I am firmly per|&s;uaded that he has a &s;incere affection for me, not|with&s;tanding the little peevi&s;hne&s;s of his behaviour to-day, which I own makes me apprehend that &s;omething mu&s;t have ruffled him extremely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>How did you like his peremptory re&s;olve, of pa&s;&s;ing the whole &s;ummer in Dor&s;et|&s;hire?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not at all, I confe&s;s; 'tis frightful to think of it&mdash;though there is a tolerable neighbour|hood&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of empty hou&s;es.&mdash;No creature &s;tays at their family &s;eats, now-a-days, unle&s;s it be &s;ome antiquated Dowager, who, like an old Gothic corner cupboard, remains fixed to the freehold.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I vow I won't go into the country&mdash;'tis quite <HI>mauvais ton&mdash;</HI>except you'll come with us; and then we'll fly about to all the bathing-places, and give a ma&s;querade at one of them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB REF="54">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould like to pa&s;s a few weeks &s;o, well enough;&mdash;and, indeed, my dear, you'll be quite forgotten, if you don't do &s;omething in that way. But are you &s;ure that Mr. Woodley would like it? for I mu&s;t &s;ay, though I a&s;k your pardon, Lady Mary, he is dull&mdash;ab&s;olutely dull, indeed, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I own, of late he has been rather gloomy;&mdash;but he is va&s;tly good-natured, and never before refu&s;ed any reque&s;t of mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That may be:&mdash;but had Mr. Bromley talked to me in the &s;ame manner&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You would have loved him ju&s;t as well as you do now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are admirable at gue&s;&s;ing, my dear;&mdash;for as that &s;ame romantic notion of love never was the band of our connexion&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;tartle me, Mrs. Bromley. Mar|riage without love mu&s;t &s;urely be a &s;tate of the greate&s;t unhappine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I don't feel in the lea&s;t unhappy.&mdash;Convenience is the be&s;t matrimonial cement, and keeps many couples together for years, who&s;e love did not out-la&s;t the honey-moon.&mdash;But the&s;e are my&s;teries, into which you &s;eem not yet initiated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope I &s;hall never know them by experience.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Loui&s;a.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear &s;i&s;ter&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(&s;ees Mrs.</HI> Bromley)</STAGE> I thought you were alone; I had &s;omething in parti|cular to tell you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You alarm me va&s;tly, Loui&s;a!&mdash;What is the matter, my dear? You know I keep no &s;ecrets from Mrs. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Another time, Lady Mary. Family affairs&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="55">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, my dear, make no &s;tranger of me!&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I hope Mountfort has jilted he<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc; I die to know.&mdash;Has the gallant Colonel de&s;erted, my dear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel Mountfort, Madam, is no way concerned in the pre&s;ent que&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Then I would not give &s;ixpence for the whole &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You look di&s;tre&s;&s;ed, Loui&s;a!&mdash;What can have happened? I'm all impatience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Though I had rather be excu&s;ed, Lady Mary, yet as you pre&s;s &s;o earne&s;tly to know, my Uncle&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>P&s;ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has in&s;i&s;ted on my marrying&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not him&s;elf, hope?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Giddy creature! I Whom, my dear Loui&s;a?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coun&s;ellor Belford.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is that all? I think it a mon&s;trous good match.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mon&s;trous, indeed!&mdash;Why, he's fifty, at lea&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fifty! fiddle-&s;tick! What does that &s;ignify? He is rich enough for three&s;core; and money, money, my dear, qualifies all di&s;|proportions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is by much too &s;erious a &s;ubject for je&s;ting, Mrs. Bromley.&mdash;But Sir William is not your &s;ole Guardian, Loui&s;a; and your brother, I am certain, will never con&s;ent to &s;acrifice you to his uncle's caprice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would not, on any account, my dear &s;i&s;ter, have my brother oppo&s;e Sir William in any thing, as he is already but too much offended with him. Be&s;ides, I am in hopes that there will not be any occa&s;ion for his interpo&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>She's coming round, I find.</P>
<PB N="50" REF="56">
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Bromley, Madam, has &s;ent the car|riage, and de&s;ires to &s;peak with you, at home, im|mediately.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>I'm glad of the relea&s;e.&mdash;What now can he po&s;&s;ibly want with me? But I am all obedience, though it breaks my heart to leave you. But I &s;hall return quickly, before any one &s;its down to Loo.&mdash;And &s;o, my dear, <STAGE><HI>(to</HI> Loui&s;a)</STAGE> I leave you to &s;ettle your important matters, which &s;hould be &s;oon determined, were you my &s;i&s;ter.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank Heaven, I am not!&mdash;She is levity it&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her lightne&s;s, Loui&s;a, extends no farther than her manners:&mdash;her morals are irre|proachable; and when the mind is untainted, its gaiety, like a coloured trimming to a grave &s;uit, &s;erves only to enliven it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are too partial, &s;i&s;ter; for I much fear that you will one day di&s;cover Mrs. Bromley's manners and morals to be <HI>both of a piece.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more upon the &s;ubject, at pre|&s;ent!&mdash;and in truth I wonder how you can have &s;pirits to talk of any thing el&s;e but your own melan|choly &s;ituation.&mdash;Married to Belford! to your Grandfather!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould be &s;ad, indeed, if &s;uch a marriage was to take place;&mdash;but my <HI>Intended</HI> has generou&s;ly con&s;ented to break off the match, at my reque&s;t, and to &s;creen me from Sir William's di&s;plea&s;ure, at the &s;ame time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then the old Barri&s;ter is charming, and I think I could be a little in love with him my&s;elf. But I cannot &s;ubmit to this new in&s;ult from Sir William! What could he mean by di&s;|po&s;ing of you without deigning to con&s;ult Mr. Woodley? I &s;hall in&s;i&s;t upon an explanation of his conduct.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="51" REF="57">
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I again intreat you, Lady Mary, not to involve my brother farther with Sir William&mdash;you do not know the con&s;equences.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am quite weary of all this temporiz|ing, Loui&s;a; and as you are &s;afe on &s;hore, you mu&s;t allow me to guide the helm for my&s;elf, at pre&s;ent.&mdash;You'll permit me, at lea&s;t, to acquaint Mr. Woodley with his uncle's contemptuous neglect of him in this matter, which I &s;hall go and do directly.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>changes to Sir</HI> WILLIAM<HI>'s Apartments.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> WILLIAM <HI>and</HI> WATERS.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, for once, Waters, I will ac|knowledge my&s;elf the happie&s;t man in England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waters.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am proud to hear that your Honour is &s;o well plea&s;ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, I am plea&s;ed, and I won't be plea&s;ed alone&mdash;they &s;hall be plea&s;ed too!&mdash;They &s;hall have a noble &s;ervice of plate!&mdash;Loui&s;a de&s;erves every thing&mdash;&s;he behaved like an angel! I thought I &s;hould have had more trouble with her; but though it be &s;trange, it is certainly true, that all girls like to be married.</P>
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel Mountfort, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall be glad to &s;ee him.&mdash;Wa't on him up, Waters. <STAGE><HI>(Exeunt</HI> Waters <HI>and Servant)</HI></STAGE> The Colonel is a very good young man, as young men go, at pre&s;ent&mdash;but nothing to compare to what his father was.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> COLONEL <HI>and</HI> WATERS.</STAGE>
<P>I am very glad to &s;ee you, my young friend. Set chairs, Waters.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Waters.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am much obliged to you, Sir William, and happy to perceive by your looks that all in|quiries after your health mu&s;t be &s;uperfluous.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thank you, Sir!&mdash;I fancy, indeed, I do look tolerably well, for &s;erenity of mind goes a great way towards clearing up the countenance; and I do not know when my &s;pirits have ever been &s;o harmo|nized, as at this moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>How fortunate!&mdash;May I flatter my&s;elf, Sir William, that the pre&s;ent happy temper of your mind will a&s;&s;i&s;t my &s;uit, and render you propitious!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Propitious! Non&s;en&s;e.&mdash;You are an idle young rogue!&mdash;With &s;uch a noble fortune as yours&mdash;But I won't &s;cold, now.&mdash;You have been on the Turf, I &s;uppo&s;e, or fleeced at the Gaming-table?&mdash;But I hope the <HI>Terra Firma</HI> is &s;afe. I &s;hould be grieved to &s;ee my old friend's e&s;tate in the hands of knaves or &s;harpers.&mdash;What &s;um do you want? I know you to be a man of honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You quite amaze me, Sir, by &s;u&s;picions which, I will be bold to &s;ay, are unworthy both of Sir William Woodley and me. I am no gam|bler, Sir, nor have I di&s;&s;ipated the noble inheri|tance derived from my ance&s;tors.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am heartily glad of it, Sir!&mdash;I a&s;k your pardon, young man.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> What the deuce, then, can he want from me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I were &s;o unfortunately weak, as you for a moment &s;eemed to imagine, the re&s;pect I bear you, would have prevented my applying to you upon &s;uch an occa&s;ion, as your good opinion, Sir, is of the greate&s;t con&s;equence to my happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>There you are wrong, Colonel;&mdash;you had much better apply to me, than to any one el&s;e.&mdash;I am no cent. per cent. man&mdash;I never received a &s;hilling intere&s;t from any friend in my life; and I have my doubts whether I &s;hould even take it from the Funds, now that the Nation is &s;o poor.&mdash;But come, Colonel, if you don't want money, in what other way can I po&s;&s;ibly &s;erve you? I have no in|tere&s;t at Court.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="53" REF="59">
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have an intere&s;t, Sir, in what is far dearer to me than either wealth or preferment:&mdash;your lovely niece, Loui&s;a, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Thank Heaven, &s;he is better di&s;po&s;ed of!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You pau&s;e!&mdash;Do not keep me on the rack, Sir William.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was only recollecting my&s;elf.&mdash;Am much obliged to you, Sir, for the honour&mdash;I think that's the phra&s;e&mdash;you intend my niece; but &s;he's married, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>Married, Sir William!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir,&mdash;married, and &s;ettled in the country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>This raillery is rather cruel, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never joke, Sir.&mdash;I have pa&s;&s;ed my word that &s;he &s;hall be married this day &s;e'nnight; and if all the Emperors, Kings, Princes, and Po|tentates in Europe, nay the Great Mogul him&s;elf, were to demand her in marriage, William Woodley would not forfeit his promi&s;e: &s;o that married &s;he is, to all intents and purpo&s;es, my gay Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>And has Mi&s;s Woodley con&s;ented, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, to be &s;ure; I force no-body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Confu&s;ion!&mdash;Impo&s;&s;ible, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;hould you think &s;o? She is a mode&s;t, dutiful girl. It would be hard, indeed, if I was to have no comfort in my family. But don't be di&s;heartened, Colonel! Many a gallant &s;oldier has met with a repul&s;e, before now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you could conceive the tenderne&s;s of my affection for Mi&s;s Woodley, Sir, you would not treat my &s;ufferings &s;o &s;lightly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>It may be a di&s;appointment, to be &s;ure, Sir, for &s;he is a fine young woman, I confe&s;s; but my friend has her, Sir, and you mu&s;t think of her no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="54" REF="60">
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is not in my power to obey your injunc|tion.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I wi&s;h it were, fal&s;e and ungrateful girl!&mdash;But pray, Sir, who is the envied man &s;o doubly ble&s;&s;ed in your friend&s;hip and Mi&s;s Wood|ley's love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's a &s;ecret, Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>That, I think, I have a right to know, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! you want to exerci&s;e your va|lour a little&mdash;&s;a, &s;a, &s;a,&mdash;by challenging your ri|val? But keep your prowe&s;s for the common foe: we cannot &s;pare a &s;oldier, at pre&s;ent, Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>This treatment is unlike your&s;elf, Sir Wil|liam. But Mi&s;s Woodley, I &s;uppo&s;e, will inform me;&mdash;I pre&s;ume &s;he is not bound to keep the &s;ecret.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>There you are wrong again, my young hero; for &s;he really is bound by the &s;tronge&s;t of all po&s;&s;ible ties&mdash;the not knowing it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Col.</SPEAKER>
<P>You cannot now be &s;erious, Sir; and I will try if I have yet power enough over Loui&s;a's heart to make her &s;o&mdash;for I will know my rival. Adieu, Sir William!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;ervant, Colonel Huff-Cap. What a hot-brained boy! I am doubly glad Loui&s;a has e&s;caped him:&mdash;I would have no pa&s;&s;ionate man in the family, but my&s;elf. How lucky 'tis that Loui&s;a does not know her hu&s;band's name!&mdash;Wo|men &s;hould ever be kept in ignorance, to prevent mi&s;chief. I have conducted this bu&s;ine&s;s mo&s;t ad|mirably!&mdash;I have &s;ome doubts, however, whether my nephew &s;hould not be made acquainted with it; but he does not de&s;erve my confidence, and he &s;han't vex me now.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> BELFORD. <HI>Sir</HI> WILLIAM <HI>runs and em|braces him.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Are all things going on bri&s;kly and cleverly, as they &s;hould do, my dear nephew?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="61">
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;wifte&s;t bowl does not always hit the jack, Sir William; and "fair and &s;oftly" is an e&s;tabli&s;hed maxim in the Law.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, we mu&s;t &s;ubmit; but I hope you'll u&s;e as much di&s;patch as po&s;&s;ible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Di&s;patch</HI> is a term, Sir, not to be found in any Law Dictionary that I know of; and I fancy it will be a long time before the matters you talk of will be di&s;patched.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, &s;urely you have a mind to try my temper, with your fair and &s;oftly! But if you knew as much as I do, you would, perhaps, think it worth while to mend your pace a little; for <Q>many things fall out between the cup and lip,</Q> Mr. Belford.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>So you'll find pre&s;ently.&mdash;The mo&s;t material point in this important affair does not appear to be yet adju&s;ted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now&mdash;what can he mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>There can be no marriage without the con&s;ent of parties; and I don't find that Mi&s;s Woodley&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I was not in the mo&s;t heavenly tem|per, you would put me in a rage. Have I not told you, Sir, that &s;he had no con&s;ent, no choice, but what I plea&s;e to give? And in twenty years ac|quaintance, have you ever known me &s;ay an untruth, Sir? My niece is all compliance and gentlene&s;s; and you'll be a very happy man, my dear nephew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould be unworthy of happine&s;s, if I could enjoy it on &s;uch terms, Sir William.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what's the matter, Belford?&mdash;Your head &s;eems to be turned with your good for|tune, and you want to turn mine. No man that is unworthy can be happy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>In &s;hort, Sir William&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, that's the thing&mdash;now you talk &s;en&s;e! I like <HI>in &s;hort&mdash;</HI>&s;tick to that, my friend. If
<PB N="56" REF="62">
you want more clerks, don't value expence, I'll clear all co&s;ts&mdash;You know I hate the Law's delay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>No law, but that of honour, has any thing to do in this ca&s;e, Sir William; and however irk&s;ome the ta&s;k, I mu&s;t beg you will per|mit me to undeceive you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you acknowledge you have de|ceived me? I am thunder-&s;truck!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my good friend&mdash;'tis you that have deceived your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your propo&s;ition is fal&s;e, Sir. I never deceived my&s;elf, nor any one el&s;e, &s;ince I was born, Sir. I &s;corn and abhor deceit, Mr. Belford. But come, Sir, let me know what all this round-about tends to? De&s;pi&s;e the chicanery of your profe&s;&s;ion, and &s;peak as if you was a witne&s;s on the table&mdash;not a Lawyer at the bar, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I fear I &s;hall rather appear a criminal at the bar to you, at pre&s;ent, Sir William.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, then, you are married, I &s;uppo&s;e?&mdash;have a wife already? Nay, don't &s;mile, Sir, there is no joke in this matter; and you ought to have been hanged, if you had married my niece.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think &s;o too, though not upon the ac|count you mention, as I give you my honour I have no wife; and if I continue in my pre&s;ent mood, may venture to &s;ay that I never &s;hall have one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mighty well, mighty ill, Mr. Belford! You have rewarded my &s;incere friendly attachment&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>With true gratitude, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't offer to &s;ay &s;o. What! to &s;purn my niece with twenty thou&s;and pounds! Let me tell you, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;he is much too good for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why really I begin to think &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I rejoice, therefore, my dear friend&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, don't rejoice. I am not your friend, nor ever will be your friend. You have
<PB N="57" REF="63">
broke my heart&mdash;fru&s;trated all my &s;chemes&mdash;di&s;ap|pointed my niece.&mdash;Poor girl, I feel for her!&mdash;Young minds are ea&s;ily broken by grief.&mdash;You will have much to an&s;wer for on her account, I a&s;&s;ure you, Mr. Belford.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould have much more to an&s;wer for to Mi&s;s Woodley, Sir William, if I did not decline the match.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Decline! Zounds, Sir, I won't bear &s;o contemptuous an expre&s;&s;ion!&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> I wi&s;h I had not been quite &s;o peremptory with the Colonel.&mdash;If I could bring my&s;elf to un&s;ay what I have once ut|tered, I would give Loui&s;a to Colonel Mount&s;ort, to vex you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I agree with you, Sir William, that it would be a more &s;uitable match.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't agree with me, Mr. Belford, I won't &s;uffer it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Allow me at lea&s;t to &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, I won't allow you to &s;ay any thing, but yes, or no, to this &s;imple que&s;tion: Do you accept, or reject, my niece?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>The phra&s;e is rather too &s;trong, Sir; but I have already told you, that upon mature con&s;i|deration, I decline the honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Will.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confound your honour, and your con|&s;ideration too!&mdash;And now, Sir, I decline any further conver&s;ation, connection, or corre&s;pondence, with you; and &s;o, Sir, I am&mdash;no&mdash;I am not, your humble &s;ervant.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>His rage will &s;oon &s;ub&s;ide, and we &s;ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">l be as good friends as ever. I am glad his re&s;ent|ment is entirely pointed at me, as 'tis probable, that to make his niece amends for the lo&s;s of a hu&s;b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">nd &s;he did not like, he may give her one &s;he does:&mdash;and &s;o ends, exactly as it &s;hould, the matr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">monial &s;chemes of an Old Batchelor!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="58" REF="64">
SCENE <HI>changes to Mr.</HI> BROMLEY's. <HI>A Dining-Room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr. and Mrs.</HI> BROMLEY.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you would defer it till to|morrow! It will otherwi&s;e break up the a&s;&s;embly, and make a mon&s;trous bu&s;tle in the family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley</SPEAKER>
<P>A fig for the a&s;&s;embly, and the bu&s;tle, too! No, no, my &s;weet &s;impleton, bu&s;ine&s;s of &s;ome kinds brook no delay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have no right to complain of my &s;implicity, Mr. Bromley. It is thro' me that you get this money from the Woodleys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Money, child! I have never touch|ed above a thou&s;and pounds of their ca&s;h yet. This piece of paper is all I have got for &s;pending my time with a dull fool, and endeavouring to per&s;uade him that he was a Solomon, and his &s;illy wife the Queen of Sheba. But I mu&s;t be paid for my attendance and trouble, and in a few minutes I &s;hall convert this manu&s;cript into the &s;um of &s;even thou&s;and three hundred and fifty-three pounds, with co&s;ts&mdash;co&s;ts mu&s;t be added.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can have no objection to your being paid for your time and trouble, my dear. All I de&s;ire is, that you may not lay on the execution 'till to-morrow. Let us devote this evening to plea&s;ure, my dear Brommy. I am to play gold Loo to-night, and I have a certain <HI>pre&s;entiment</HI> that I &s;hall win con&s;iderably.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>As to your winning, I believe you are pretty &s;ecure in that point. You don't leave much to chance, I imagine, my dove. But tho' you might win, I &s;hall lo&s;e con&s;iderably, if this bond be not put in force this very night. I have been with Woodley's attorney, Mr. Fleece'em, a very ho|ne&s;t man, and for a &s;mall token of friend&s;hip, he has informed me, that there will be &s;ix executions in the hou&s;e to morrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="59" REF="65">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Six executions! Nay, then, they are <HI>done up,</HI> indeed, and it does not &s;ignify much keeping any further terms with them. Yet I &s;till wi&s;h you would po&s;tpone this ugly bu&s;ine&s;s, 'till we are gone to the ma&s;querade. Poor Lady Mary! it will be a &s;ad di&s;appointment to her, not to &s;hew her finery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you talk of finery, here, look at the&s;e!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(&s;hewing her Lady</HI> Mary<HI>'s ear-rings.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me &s;ee! They are Lady Mary's ear-rings!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; they were, my &s;weet innocent!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>But how came you by them? She told me they were gone to be new-&s;et.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;k no que&s;tions, but take them, and think your&s;elf happy in &s;uch a provident hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, my dear Brom|my! They are beautiful, indeed!&mdash;I have long wi&s;hed for them, I confe&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t go and expedite this bu&s;i|ne&s;s directly. Don't be frightened, dove, when the Bailiffs come in. They'll add to Lady Mary's &s;queeze, you know.&mdash;But take a little hart&s;horn in your pocket:&mdash;it will be proper for you to faint, I think.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear my acting properly.&mdash;But the carriage is at the door, and I have twenty places to call at. Shall I &s;et you down at your lawyer's, to &s;ave my dear the fatigue of walking?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>How happy am I in &s;uch a di&s;creet, tender wife!&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> A di&s;&s;embling jade!&mdash;Come, dove.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I follow, my dear Brommy.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Hateful wretch!</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FOURTH ACT.</TRAILER>
