<PB N="60" REF="66">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE, <HI>An Anti-chamber, opening into a Drawing-room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>FORWARD, <HI>with a Pencil and Pocket-book. A Foot man in the Drawing-room, placing Card-Tables for a Rout.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>FOUR gold Loo tables, with Mon&s;ters&mdash;Four p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">und four!&mdash;Two at half-crowns! Thru&s;t them to the lower end of the room, James; they are &s;eldom worth more than twelve &s;hillings a piece.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>James.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where &s;hall I fix the Whi&s;t tables, Mr. Forward?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn the Whi&s;kers! Even the gold players never make it worth a gentleman's while to &s;nuff their candles. I wi&s;h the Parliament would put down all &s;neaking games!&mdash;A man can neither win or lo&s;e a fortune with any degree of credit at them. No&mdash;Pharo, Pharo's the &s;port.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>James.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is this a Pharaoh's table, Mr. Forward?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; but &s;et that in the center, in the be&s;t place in the room. That's a Macao-table, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">ome of the <HI>birds,</HI> I fancy, will be picked pretty bare that play at it&mdash;Five pound five.&mdash;Do you hear, James? The moment the company's gone, pack up all the cards and candles, whether u&s;ed or not, and carry them to my room:&mdash;I may have occa&s;ion for them, if I &s;hould &s;ee company while I am out of place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>James.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, you leave us a few packs to make merry with in the Servants Hall, Mr. Forward? I likes a game at All <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">ours, dea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="61" REF="67">
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, &s;ervants &s;hould have their amu&s;e|ments, as well as their betters, James; &s;o you may &s;trip the Whi&s;t-tables for your own u&s;e. The Dons always take &s;nuff, and fully their cards confound|edly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>James.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank. you, thank you, Mr. Forward! Mu&s;t I carry up the candles to your room that mayn't be lighted?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly; the others will only &s;erve for my bed-chamber, or to dre&s;s by. I dete&s;t tallow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>James.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I'll do as I'm bid.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> What a thief it is! and as great a Jew to a poor fellow-&s;ervant, as if he was not the &s;ame fle&s;h and blood!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall make about twelve pieces pack|ing penny. I wi&s;h my ma&s;ter may win to-night, as I &s;hall call upon him for my wages to-morrow: and, to do him ju&s;tice, he is always ready to pay, when he has it. The Funds are low at pre&s;ent, and a prudent man &s;hould not &s;uffer his money to lie dead, e&s;pecially in &s;uch hands where it may be buried, too.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> MARY <HI>and Mr.</HI> WOODLEY.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let the ices be brought before eleven, Forward, as I wi&s;h the a&s;&s;embly to break up early. Are the bouquets come from the King's Road? Let there be a profu&s;ion of rofes in all the rooms: they are delicious, at this <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="2 letters">a&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip &s;hall be obeyed&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> for the la&s;t time by your Lady&s;hip's mo&s;t humble.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your indifference upon this occa&s;ion really amazes me, Mr. Woodley! I thought you loved your &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="62" REF="68">
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, mo&s;t tenderly, and &s;hall therefore rejoice at &s;eeing her under the protection of a wor|thy man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me! is there nothing but worth to be con&s;id<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">red, in matrimony? no allowance to be made for liking? I vow, if you had been fifty times as worthy as you are, I would never have married you, if you had not been agreeable, al&s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sweet flatterer!</P>
<STAGE>(taking her hand.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>But as the match is not to take place, his being agreeable or not is of no con&s;equence, now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't comprehend you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You don't choo&s;e to comprehend me, Mr. Woodley. But &s;till I mu&s;t &s;ay, that the indig|nity of Sir William's pre&s;uming to di&s;po&s;e of your &s;i&s;ter without your con&s;ent, is not to be endured.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are mi&s;informed, my dear. Mount|fort a&s;ked my con&s;ent, before he applied to Sir Wil|liam&mdash;I did not &s;ee you &s;ince.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mountfort is quite out of the pre&s;ent que&s;tion, I tell you, Mr. Woodley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You rave, my dear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>One of us does, that's certain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am not mad, yet, Madam&mdash;though I have enough to make me &s;o.</P>
<STAGE>(With emotion.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is too much, Mr. Woodley. Every one takes notice of your behaviour to me, of late; and wonder how I bear it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(looking gravely at her)</STAGE> Did you know what I bear&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>From me, Mr. Woodley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not from, but for, you, Mary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You terrify me! Explain your mean|ing, I intereat you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will too &s;oon cea&s;e to be a my&s;tery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, do not let me be the la&s;t to know it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="63" REF="69">
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Could every pang I now endure, be doubled to &s;ave you from the &s;hock which you mu&s;t feel, I'd bear them all, without complaining. But ruin comes on apace! and that you mu&s;t &s;hare it ag|gravates my di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ungenerous Woodley! to think I would &s;hrink from any mi&s;ery that attends on you! But &s;peak your meaning clearly&mdash;&s;u&s;pence is tor|ture&mdash;what mi&s;ery awaits us?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our fortune's gone, my Mary!&mdash;We are undone!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gone! Not all&mdash;my jointure &s;till is left.&mdash;Di&s;po&s;e of that, and let me go into retirement with you. With plea&s;ure I'll renounce all the fan|ta&s;tic gaieties of life, and find true happine&s;s in your &s;ociety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley</SPEAKER>
<P>Your noblene&s;s of mind but adds to my di&s;tre&s;s.&mdash;Your jointure! No, I will live a beggar, all my days, rather than leave you one, when I mu&s;t leave you. Somewhat may yet be done to &s;ave us from de&s;truction. I have a dependence on Mr. Bromley's friend&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>So have I;&mdash;but we mu&s;t be our own friends, my dear.&mdash;I will go into Dor&s;et&s;hire, imme|diately. Let us di&s;charge hal<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter"> our &s;ervants, and become patterns of oeconomy and conjugal happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous, charming woman! Happi|ne&s;s mu&s;t attend you, every where.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis the in&s;eparable companion of an upright heart; and my dear Woodley &s;hall &s;oon be convinced from my conduct, that chearfulne&s;s can &s;urvive gaiety, and true love make ample amends for the lo&s;s of fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;en&s;e and virtue have removed the heavie&s;t weight that hung upon my hear<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then clear your brow, my d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">ar, and let us act the la&s;t &s;cene of the farce with the &s;ame &s;pirit as the fir&s;t.</P>
<PB N="64" REF="70">
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Colonel Mountfort, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew him into my dre&s;&s;ing-room&mdash;I'll wait on him in&s;tantly.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit Serv.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't let even Colonel Mountfort perceive your dejection, my dear Woodley. We &s;hould, in kindne&s;s to our friends, conceal our &s;or|rows.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>If Mountfort has &s;ucceeded with my uncle, Loui&s;a's happine&s;s will lighten my di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not time to a&s;k an explanation of this matter, now.&mdash;But let me again intreat you to be chearful:&mdash;&s;omething tells me that our &s;itua|tion is not &s;o bad as you imagine. Let us not anti|cipate misfortune:&mdash;'tis always too &s;oon to be wretched.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will exert my utmo&s;t power, my dear, to emulate your fortitude.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>My fortitude! Ah Woodley! little do&s;t thou know the perturbation here.&mdash;Ruin comes on apace!&mdash;The &s;hock was &s;udden and &s;evere; but 'twas my love, not re&s;olution, bore me through it.&mdash;And now let me collect my&s;elf a little, and try, by Rea&s;on's &s;tandard, the value of tho&s;e joys which I re&s;ign.&mdash;Dre&s;s! Won't my little per&s;on look as well in a plain &s;ilk, as in all this finery? Vanity &s;ays, Yes.&mdash;Grandeur&mdash;what is it? A magnificent &s;ide-board, a train of u&s;ele&s;s &s;ervants, gay furniture, crouded rooms, and blazing lights, which but oppre&s;s the &s;pirits, without affording enjoyment. Elegance is not confined to &s;tate: her handmaid Neatne&s;s &s;hall pre&s;ide at our board, and render our rural fare de|licious.&mdash;Operas! Ranelagh! Plays! Ma&s;querades! A&s;&s;emblies! Company! ay, there's the rub! So|ciety! dear Society! I &s;hall not find, a Mrs. Brom|ley in Dor&s;et&s;hire; but I &s;hall have my Woodley there, and my endeavours not to let him &s;ee I grieve,
<PB N="65" REF="71">
will &s;oon make me cea&s;e to do &s;o. My re&s;olution's fixed&mdash;I'll acquaint Loui&s;a with it in&s;tantly,</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>changes to Mr.</HI> WOODLEY's <HI>Dre&s;&s;ing-room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Mr.</HI> WOODLEY, <HI>Colonel</HI> MOUNTFORT.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my honour, Colonel, I am as unable to fathom Sir William's meaning, as you can be. I am certain that no per&s;on ever propo&s;ed to me for Loui&s;a, but your&s;elf, and &s;he could not po&s;&s;ibly give her con&s;ent, before it was a&s;ked.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>This a&s;&s;urance has revived my hopes a little; but 'tis impo&s;&s;ible my heart can be at ea&s;e, till your &s;i&s;ter has pronounced my doom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>If &s;he con&s;ults her own heart, Mount|fort, you will not, I fancy, have much rea&s;on to com|plain of her &s;entence. But as &s;he is the only Oedi|pus that can expound this riddle, let us apply to her for the explanation.</P>
<STAGE>[Rings.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>You prevent my wi&s;hes, for you have an undoubted right to make the enquiry.</P>
<STAGE>Enter Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell my &s;i&s;ter I de&s;ire to &s;peak with her, immediately.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>How my heart throbs, at her ap|proach!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>For &s;hame, my gallant friend!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Woodley! when all one's happine&s;s is &s;taked on the turn of a die, who would not trem|ble when he &s;tood the ca&s;t?</P>
<STAGE>Enter Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Woodley, Sir, has ju&s;t &s;ent to let Sir William know &s;he wi&s;hes to pay her re&s;pects to him:&mdash;at her return &s;he will wait upon you.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Inhuman girl! She trifles with my anxiety&mdash;perhaps rejoices in it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="66" REF="72">
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lovers are of all beings the mo&s;t irra|tiona. I'd hazard my life that Loui&s;a has never heard of your propo&s;al to Sir William, and of cour&s;e can know nothing of your anxiety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>She will be &s;oon acquainted with both. But have not you informed her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, on my honour; I have not &s;een her &s;ince you left me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your coolne&s;s on this &s;ubject, Mr. Woodley, by no means accords with my impatience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You wrong me, Mountfort. Be a&s;&s;ur|ed, that your union with Loui&s;a is an object my heart is &s;et on; but that heart is torn to pieces, at pre&s;ent.&mdash;I cannot &s;peak&mdash;Loui&s;a never &s;tays long with her uncle&mdash;&s;he will return in a few minutes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>They will be years to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us meet her then, before &s;he goes into the drawing-room.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>changes to Sir</HI> WILLIAM<HI>'s Apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> WILLIAM.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor child! I am very &s;orry &s;he is coming&mdash;I know not what excu&s;e to make for Bel|ford&mdash;I fear it will be a grievous di&s;appointment to her.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I come, Sir, mo&s;t joyfully to tell you &s;omething that I am &s;ure will give you plea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William,</SPEAKER>
<P>My poor dear! and I have &s;ome|thing to tell you, that I am &s;ure will give you pain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir, I am &s;o much rejoiced at pre&s;ent, that there are but very few things that could render me unhappy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>So much the wor&s;e&mdash;the &s;hock will be the greater! I &s;hall never have the courage to tell her.&mdash;The &s;uddenne&s;s of this event, Loui&s;a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="67" REF="73">
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you know it, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, but too well, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You quite &s;urpri&s;e me, Sir! It is not above five minutes, &s;ince it was determined.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, 'tis more than that&mdash;above half an hour. But though matters have taken an unexpected turn, I would not have you fret, or grieve, child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>So far from it, Sir, that I am quite re|joiced, and flattered my&s;elf that you would be &s;o too, as I know it is a point you have long &s;et your heart upon;&mdash;and I mu&s;t do Lady Mary the ju&s;tice to de|clare the plan was intirely her own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Mary! I gue&s;&s;ed as much.&mdash;How did &s;he dare to thwart my &s;chemes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir, have you not always wi&s;hed that my brother and &s;i&s;ter &s;hould live in Dor&s;et&s;hire? and now that Lady Mary has, of her own accord, determined to quit London, you &s;eem offended.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Softly, &s;oftly, child; don't hurry me!&mdash;For once in my life, I perceive I am left behind.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> So, I find &s;he knows nothing of Belford, and that work is all to do, yet.&mdash;Go on, my dear! Lady Mary, you &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has, un&s;olicited by any one, re&s;olved to give up all the gaiety and di&s;&s;ipation of this town, and remain in Dor&s;et&s;hire till my brother's affairs are intirely retrieved.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>She'll not return in a hurry, then, I doubt.&mdash;I am glad of it, my dear, for your &s;ake, as well as your brother's:&mdash;air and exerci&s;e will be of great u&s;e to you.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I'm afraid &s;he'll &s;tand in need of them, when &s;he is acquainted with her mi&s;|fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, my good, dear uncle, won't you give Lady Mary credit for her prudence? and won't you permit my brother and &s;i&s;ter to take leave of you, before they go?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="68" REF="74">
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hate all forms and ceremonies, child!&mdash;They have had my leave to go into the coun|try, the&s;e three years pa&s;t; and I am le&s;s di&s;plea&s;ed with your &s;i&s;ter, for her prudent re&s;olution. And &s;o, at your reque&s;t, my dear, you may all breakfa&s;t with me before you &s;et out to-morrow.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I'll defer acquainting her till then, with Belford's be|haviour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't believe, Sir, that they can &s;et out &s;o immediately; but I am certain they will not defer a moment to accept your kind invitation, on that account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, child, &s;top! I won't have them come to me, till the very hour they are going. If I were to &s;ee your brother often, I might be weak enough to grow fond of him again; &s;o don't let him come, I charge you, 'till his boots are on. I have trouble enough on my hands for others, al|ready. You don't know what I &s;uffer on your ac|count, Loui&s;a, at this moment. But you &s;hall know all about it, when you are &s;etting off for Dor&s;et|&s;hire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>I wi&s;h I dare venture to make the good man's mind ea&s;y, with regard to me.&mdash;As I am perfectly re&s;igned to your commands, Sir, on every occa&s;ion, I hope I &s;hall never give you cau&s;e for any real trouble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>There now, &s;he'll break my heart with her mildne&s;s!&mdash;I hope for your own &s;ake you'll be re&s;igned, my dear. But go, child, and tell your brother and Lady Mary, that I &s;hall be glad to &s;ee them on the morning they are &s;etting out; but not before, upon any account whatever.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I rejoice to be the me&s;&s;enger of &s;uch glad tidings; for if he &s;ees my brother, I am certain he will &s;erve him.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="69" REF="75">
SCENE, <HI>a Drawing-room. Card-tables, with Com|pany at Play.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Lady</HI> MARY, LOUISA, <HI>Mr.</HI> BELFORD, <HI>Colonel</HI> MOUNTFORT.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fifty pieces on the rubber!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>A bet, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Pam flu&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;eldom deal, I think, without one, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Pam box can be&s;t an&s;wer that hint, Madam; for this is the fir&s;t guinea I have been able to put into it, this whole winter.&mdash;But you lo&s;e, at pre&s;ent, Madam, and therefore have leave to &s;peak.&mdash;Plea&s;e to mark the Loo, Madam&mdash;'tis ju&s;t &s;ixty guineas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to Bel&s;ord.)</STAGE>
<P>How much am 'I obliged to you, my excellent friend, for &s;o generou&s;ly &s;aving me from the pain of offending the be&s;t of uncles!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>And let me join my gratitude, Sir, for your having &s;o kindly removed, I hope, the only ob&s;tacle to my happine&s;s, by relea&s;ing Sir William from his promi&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>I heartily wi&s;h he may be inclined to transfer his favour to you, Sir.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> BROMLEY.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear cou&s;in, here's a place for you! The Mon&s;ters mu&s;t come in with Mrs. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll wait upon you, in a moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Mon&s;ters po&s;itively &s;hall not come in, 'till 'tis a &s;ingle &s;take;&mdash;and then I &s;hall never have a flu&s;h after, I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Bromley, I have a thou&s;and things to &s;ay to you of the utmo&s;t importance. I wi&s;h you would not play, to-night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not play! you mu&s;t excu&s;e me, indeed, Lady Mary! Be&s;ides, we &s;hall have time
<PB N="70" REF="76">
enough to talk over tho&s;e &s;ame important matters, you know, at the Ma&s;querade.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall not go, to-night, and have &s;omething &s;o intere&s;ting to tell you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>'Tis impo&s;&s;ible &s;he &s;hould &s;u&s;pect any thing.&mdash;Your Lady&s;hip knows I hate melancholy &s;tories.&mdash; <STAGE>(to the Table)</STAGE> Is the Loo over?&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I can't help feeling a little aukward, when I &s;peak to her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Another flu&s;h, as I live! I don't be|lieve we &s;hall have a &s;ingle &s;take, the&s;e two hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Quadrille.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip's ba&s;ted&mdash;you trumpted the King of Diamonds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Quadrille.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then, Madam? Here take the Diamond, I have my game without it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Quadrille.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Madam&mdash;a renounce is a Bea&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Quadrille.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't &s;ubmit to it.&mdash;Judgment! <HI>Several.</HI> Your Lady&s;hip's a Bea&s;t! a Bea&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a racket they make, at this pal|try play! Not above a crown a-fi&s;h, I dare &s;wear!&mdash;The Loo is ju&s;t two hundred and forty guineas!&mdash;Deal, Madam.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> WOODLEY, <HI>and joins</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not keep your promi&s;e, Bromley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, no, indeed, Madam! I cannot po&s;&s;ibly think of ru&s;ticating my&s;elf with your Lady&s;hip;&mdash;but if any of the &s;ummer camps &s;hould happen to lie near you, I may give you a call, <HI>en pa&s;&s;ant,</HI> to &s;ee how love and a cottage agree with you.&mdash;Will you never let me in, Mrs. Henpeck?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Madam, I wi&s;h you had been in my place, the whole evening, with all my heart! I have lo&s;t near three hundred pounds in it.&mdash;Heigh|ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I had vainly flattered my&s;elf, it &s;eems, that my company might have rendered the country
<PB N="71" REF="77">
pa&s;&s;able, at lea&s;t, to one who profe&s;&s;ed her&s;elf my friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I always thought your Lady&s;hip very romantic.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I wi&s;h &s;he would not teaze me &s;o!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>This &s;hock is much &s;everer to me, than the fir&s;t I felt, as friends were dearer to me than fortune.&mdash;But let me ri&s;e above her worthle&s;&s;ne&s;s, nor let her &s;ee how her unkindne&s;s wounds me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lurched at four! 'tis confounded hard!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I bet you three to one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash; <STAGE>(to Mrs. Bromley)</STAGE> Will Mr. Bromley be here, to-night?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly.&mdash;Sooner than you wi&s;h, I fancy.</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(looking earne&s;tly at Mrs. Bromley)</STAGE>
<P>Pray, Mrs. Bromley, did you hire tho&s;e ear-rings from my jeweller? I'm glad now, he did not alter them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have never yet been under the nece&s;&s;ity of hiring jewels, Madam, whatever other people may have been. But though the &s;etting of the&s;e is not altered, Madam, the property is;&mdash;for they are mine, at pre&s;ent, I a&s;&s;ure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll pardon me, Mrs. Bromley.&mdash;Mr. Woodley, pray are not tho&s;e my ear-rings?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>They were, my dear.&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> This is ungenerous of Bromley!&mdash;I will explain this mat|ter another time, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Mr. Woodley, it requires but little explanation. Lady Mary is not &s;o much a child as not to know, that, in this country, and in the&s;e times, property quickly changes hands, from tho&s;e who have &s;quandered their own fortunes, and po&s;&s;ibly that of others, to tho&s;e who have been more prudent, and le&s;s lavi&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="72" REF="78">
<SPEAKER>3d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Loo is over, Mrs. Bromley.&mdash;Bring the Mon&s;ters, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought it would never be a &s;ingle &s;take!</P>
<STAGE>(&s;its down to the table.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>Her unkindne&s;s would be in|&s;upportable, did not the in&s;olence of it render her de&s;picable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you think, Mi&s;s Woodley, that Lady Mary looks uncommonly grave, this evening?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You will not be &s;urpri&s;ed at her &s;eriou&s;|ne&s;s, when I tell you that &s;he has determined on quitting London immediately, and retiring with my brother into Dor&s;et&s;hire. I &s;hall go with them, Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I &s;hall as certainly follow my leader. Sir William can have no objection to my being can|toned in the neighbourhood of Woodley Park, I pre&s;ume?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Four by honours, again! This is the fourth time you have dealt them, in the rubber. Six|teen out of twenty, are odds that Demoivre could not play again&s;t.&mdash;There's your money, there's your money, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;double or quit with your Lord|&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know I am a bubble, but I hate to cut a lo&s;er.&mdash;'Tis a bet, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two Pams, as I hope to be &s;aved!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie, Madam, don't &s;wear! 'tis va&s;tly ill-bred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis much wor&s;e breeding to cheat, Mrs. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mean creature! I &s;corn your words.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hould begin by &s;corning mean actions, Madam. But you &s;han't take up the Loo, I a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;I have long &s;u&s;pected you of &s;uch tricks.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="73" REF="79">
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o have I.&mdash;Heigh-ho!&mdash;&s;he has got a deal of my money.&mdash;Heigh-ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And of mine too, I a&s;&s;ure you;&mdash;but her &s;urpri&s;ing luck is now clearly accounted for.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't touch another card with &s;uch vulgar, &s;u&s;picious wretches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>We have renounced you fir&s;t, Madam;&mdash;&s;o if you plea&s;e to ri&s;e from the table, Madam, and I'll take care that you &s;hall never &s;it down to any other where-ever I am pre&s;ent, I a&s;&s;ure you, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Put all the Mon&s;ters out, at once.&mdash;Heigh-ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(ri&s;ing in a pa&s;&s;ion, and addre&s;&s;ing Lady</HI> Mary)</STAGE>
<P>I did not think your Lady&s;hip would &s;tand tamely by, and &s;uffer me to be in&s;ulted in your hou&s;e; but 'tis the la&s;t time I &s;hall ever come into it, I promi&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall take care that you &s;han't break that promi&s;e, if you &s;hou'd happen to forget it, Mrs. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Bromley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;peak like an oracle, with|out con&s;ciou&s;ne&s;s, Madam; for this is the la&s;t night you will ever have any authority here, believe me: and &s;o I leave your Lady&s;hip to your future rural felicity.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(to</HI> Loui&s;a)</STAGE>
<P>Was there ever &s;o &s;udden and extraordinary a change in any human creature!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis rather a di&s;covery, than a metamor|pho&s;e, my dear Lady Mary!&mdash;I have long &s;een through Mrs. Bromley's ma&s;k&mdash;'twas only made of gauze.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FORWARD, <HI>and &s;peaks to Mr.</HI> WOODLEY.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>There are &s;ome Gentlemen below, Sir, who, though not invited, in&s;i&s;t upon coming up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Admit them, directly&mdash;all Gentlemen are welcome.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="74" REF="80">
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould have done &s;o, Sir, but that the&s;e Gentlemen don't &s;eem to be well enough dre&s;&s;ed for my Lady's a&s;&s;embly&mdash;They are but Bailiffs, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;traction! my di&s;grace is public, now!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE><HI>(to</HI> Forward)</STAGE>
<P>At who&s;e &s;uit do they come here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Forward.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think they mentioned Mr. Bromley, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible! he is the very friend I thought of applying to, in my pre&s;ent difficulties.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be too confident, Mr. Woodley. I know that fellow to be a con&s;ummate knave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't let your &s;pirits &s;ink, my dear Woodley.&mdash;We'll inquire into the matter, and ac|commodate it immediately.&mdash;I beg your Lady&s;hip not to be alarmed&mdash;every thing &s;hall be &s;ettled, directly. Try to &s;upport your &s;i&s;ter's &s;inking heart, my dear Loui&s;a.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exeunt</HI> Colonel, Woodley, <HI>and</HI> Belford.</STAGE>
<STAGE>[Loui&s;a <HI>&s;eems to comfort Lady</HI> Mary, <HI>who is in Tears, and both go out together.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bailiffs, did the fellow &s;ay? Egad, I'll decamp in time.</P>
<STAGE>[ri&s;es.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t not &s;tir, 'till the rubber is out, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip mu&s;t excu&s;e me!&mdash;Such incidents are &s;o common, to be &s;ure, in the pre&s;ent times, that they cea&s;e to be &s;candalous; but that does not prevent my being affected by them. I &s;hall re|member that &s;even to four are the points of our game, and for debts of honour, my Lord, you'll always find me &s;olvent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Whi&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e &s;cenes are apt to affect me, too, Charles!&mdash;I never could &s;tand them.&mdash;Peers are pri|vileged from &s;uch &s;ympathies; &s;o let us counter|march
<PB N="75" REF="81">
down the back-&s;tairs, together, or we may be lurched, though we are &s;even.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt 2d and 3d Whi&s;t.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall faint, if I &s;ee them!&mdash;I mu&s;t go, Ladies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us have another round, Madam! We are all married women, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My antipathy to the&s;e harpies was con|tracted while I was a widow, Madam.&mdash;'Tis your deal, Madam&mdash;Poor Lady Mary!&mdash;Heigh-ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, poor Lady Mary, I &s;ay too;&mdash;tho' to be &s;ure, one cannot have any great compa&s;&s;ion for &s;uch an extravagant woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Compa&s;&s;ion! No, truly!&mdash;Such &s;uppers after her routs! though I was never a&s;ked to one of them. That cheat Bromley was one of her chief favourites, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is gone out of the room, as I live, without making the lea&s;t apology.&mdash;Did you ever hear of &s;uch rudene&s;s! I'll never vi&s;it her again.&mdash;Heigh-ho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor I.&mdash;'Tis time to break up, indeed, when the Lady of the hou&s;e has retired!&mdash;I'll carry off this Pam, to triumph over that rude wretch, Bromley. I &s;hall have the honour of &s;eeing you all, to-morrow night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Omnes.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>My coach was not ordered 'till twelve.&mdash;Will you carry me to Lady Freaki&s;h's rout? They never meet there, 'till eleven.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>With plea&s;ure.&mdash;But I in&s;i&s;t upon telling the &s;tory of the Woodleys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I of Mrs. Bromley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Loo.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I have nothing left to do, but to count my lo&s;&s;es.&mdash;Heigh-ho!</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="76" REF="82">
SCENE <HI>changes to Sir</HI> WILLIAM'S <HI>Apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> WILLIAM <HI>and</HI> WATERS.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why didn't you &s;ay I was gone to bed? She'll break my re&s;t, for this night, at lea&s;t. She has heard of her misfortune, I fear.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Sir!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>&s;ir William.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Yes, yes, 'tis all out, now.&mdash;Nay, my dear child, don't take on &s;o&mdash;you'll break my heart, if you do.&mdash;'I was not my &s;ault, Loui&s;a.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't talk or think of faults, now, Sir.&mdash;You know that before this di&s;graceful event happen|ed in the family&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you talk of it in &s;uch a me|lancholy &s;train, child;&mdash;'tis no di&s;grace, I tell you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis too public to be concealed, Sir. The Bailiffs are but this moment gone out of the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>What hou&s;e? This hou&s;e? Your brother's hou&s;e? What! have they carried him to pri&s;on? I thought it would come to this.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir&mdash;Colonel Mountfort gene|rou&s;ly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>What had he to do with it? Why &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">olonel Mountfort, or any one el&s;e? Why didn't they &s;end to me?&mdash;But what have I to do wi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">h your brother, child? He &s;hould have gone to pri<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>He would not long have langui&s;hed there, Sir believe me; a broken heart would &s;oon have r<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">a&s;ed him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha, p&s;ha&mdash;with your broken heart&mdash;You play the fool with me!&mdash;My nephew pe|ri&s;h in a ga<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="2 letters">! But he has brought it all on him&s;elf, you know, child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I grant that his imprudence, Sir, has ex|ceeded every thing, but your good-nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="77" REF="83">
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confound my good-nature! it is for ever bringing me into &s;crapes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>And bringing others out of them, my dear uncle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, well&mdash;I want Belford, now, extremely!&mdash;Every thing falls out unlucky!&mdash;But what of Colonel Mountfort, child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was going to tell you, Sir, that he be|came &s;ecurity for my brother, on the in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's noble! for he did not know that I would di&s;charge the debt.&mdash;Nay, for that mat|ter, I don't know that I &s;hall&mdash;I promi&s;e nothing&mdash;but I like this action of the Colonel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I rejoice to hear it, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay! then perhaps you like the Co|lonel? Be hone&s;t, &s;peak out.&mdash;I &s;hould be glad to make you &s;ome amends for a lo&s;s you don't yet know of;&mdash;but I can conceal it no longer.&mdash;Bel&s;ord has declared off!&mdash;but he is unworthy your re&s;entment. The Colonel's father was my friend, and a noble fellow he was!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>And his &s;on is every way worthy of &s;uch a father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I rejoice to find her &s;o ea&s;ily reconciled.&mdash;Well, that matter is &s;ettled, for the pre&s;ent.&mdash;But are you certain that your brother and Lady Mary will hold their re&s;olution of retiring to Dor&s;et&s;hire?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know, Sir, it was their determined purpo&s;e, before this misfortune happened.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's &s;omething in their favour, to be &s;ure, and I'm glad you told me of it.&mdash;One good act of choice, is worth all the virtues of nece&s;&s;ity, in the world.&mdash;I &s;hould be glad to make their minds ea&s;y, to-night&mdash;But they'd thank me, and talk to me, and di&s;compo&s;e me, and I &s;hould lo&s;e my night's re&s;t&mdash;for I hate thanks.&mdash;I &s;hould be glad to &s;ee Co|lonel
<PB N="78" REF="84">
Mountfort:&mdash;his behaviour has &s;hewn a re&s;pect to me, and the family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>You will meet him now, at my brother's, Sir, where your pre&s;ence will make them all happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, child, I can deny you no|thing.&mdash;I like to make people happy, when they'll a&s;&s;i&s;t me in doing &s;o, them&s;elves; without which the be&s;t endeavours are but labour in vain.&mdash;But the country is the place!&mdash;You mu&s;t &s;ettle in the coun|try, Loui&s;a!&mdash;There is no &s;afety for good folks in London, believe me, child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould hope, Sir, that with prudence and virtue one might be &s;afe any where.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>A fig for your prudence&mdash;ay, and for virtue too, again&s;t example! Example, child, is the ruin of us all. We naturally &s;trive to ape tho&s;e that are called our Betters, and &s;o become wor&s;e than we otherwi&s;e &s;hould be.&mdash;But this is no time for mo|ralizing. Do you &s;tep in and tell your brother I am coming. I'll ju&s;t wrap my cloak round me and follow you.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;everally.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE <HI>changes to Mr.</HI> WOODLEY's <HI>Dre&s;&s;ing-room.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Mr.</HI> WOODLEY, <HI>Mr.</HI> BELFORD, <HI>and Colonel</HI> MOUNTFORT.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Belford.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fear not, my gallant Colonel! Mr. Woodley &s;hall have ample vengeance upon that &s;coundrel Bromley; for as he has evidently altered the date of the bond, we &s;hall find a way to reward his ingenuity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not whether I am mo&s;t a&s;toni&s;h|ed at his villany, or at my own weakne&s;s in being duped by it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>The uprightne&s;s of your own heart, my dear Woodley, is the be&s;t excu&s;e for your credulity.</P>
<STAGE><PB N="79" REF="85">
<HI>Enter Lady</HI> MARY, <HI>and</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Loui&s;a.</SPEAKER>
<P>I come the happy me&s;&s;enger of joyful tidings! My dear good uncle&mdash;But he's here.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> WILLIAM.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm glad to meet you here, all to|gether, for I have bu&s;ine&s;s with every one of you, jointly and &s;everally.&mdash;And fir&s;t for you, Colonel, I am very much obliged to you, Sir, and I &s;corn to be obliged to any man, without making him &s;ome return for his kindne&s;s. I therefore make you a pre|&s;ent I refu&s;ed you, a few hours ago, for the &s;ake of old Sir Doubtful Deliberation there.&mdash;But do you take Loui&s;a, and for aught I know, you may make her as good a hu&s;band as he would have done.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Colonel.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall u&s;e my be&s;t endeavours, Sir, to de&s;erve&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right&mdash;&s;tick to that.&mdash;No thanks, but de&s;erve as much as ever you can.&mdash;And as for you, Mr. Belford, though I am confoundedly angry with you, I mu&s;t get you to &s;ettle this young man's affairs; his debts of <HI>honour,</HI> his <HI>po&s;t obits,</HI> &amp;c.; though perhaps it may be only affording him an opportunity for <HI>deranging</HI> them again.&mdash;That's the modern phra&s;e, I think, for being over-head-and-ears in debt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Woodley.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ufferings my follies have brought upon me, Sir, and the remembrance of your gene|ro&s;ity, will remain too &s;trongly impre&s;&s;ed on my mind, to admit of my relap&s;ing into my former errors; as that would be adding ingratitude to ex|travagance, and vice to folly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I hope &s;o.&mdash;Kindne&s;s &s;hould be the &s;tronge&s;t tie to a generous mind, and I &s;u&s;pect you not of any ba&s;ene&s;s in your nature;&mdash;though, to be &s;ure, you have &s;hewn a plentiful lack of wi&s;dom in your conduct. But misfortunes
<PB N="80" REF="86">
make Solomons of us all!&mdash;And now, Madam, <STAGE><HI>(to Lady</HI> Mary)</STAGE> to &s;hew you that the merit of your vo|luntary retirement into the country, is not lo&s;t upon me, I make you a pre&s;ent of this hou&s;e, for your winter re&s;idence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your kindne&s;s, Sir,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop there&mdash;I won't be thanked&mdash;I wi&s;h to do as I would be done by; and as I &s;hould not like to be confined in the fine&s;t place in the world, not even Woodley Park, I would not impo&s;e &s;uch a re&s;traint on one who I doubt not will hereafter merit my indulgence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gratitude overwhelms me, Sir!&mdash;I cannot &s;peak my &s;en&s;e of your goodne&s;s as it de&s;erves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir William.</SPEAKER>
<P>So much the better!&mdash;There are nobler ways of &s;hewing one's &s;entiments.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>They &s;hall be demon&s;trated in my future conduct, Sir; for the virtue that ari&s;es from the conviction of pa&s;t errors, mu&s;t be at once &s;incere, and permanent.</P>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
